00:01:21.030 --> 00:01:22.360
thank you everyone for coming.

00:01:22.360 --> 00:01:26.500
As Paulette mentioned, this
is the Ninth Annual GIS Day

00:01:26.500 --> 00:01:30.010
at the Library of Congress,
and GIS has come a long,

00:01:30.010 --> 00:01:33.460
long way here in
those nine years.

00:01:33.460 --> 00:01:36.910
For those not familiar
with it, GIS really started

00:01:36.910 --> 00:01:41.200
about 20 years ago here at the
library with a single license

00:01:41.200 --> 00:01:45.390
in a single office down in GNM
with a man, Gary Fitzpatrick,

00:01:45.390 --> 00:01:49.180
who did a lot of work and a lot
of mapping and tried to kind

00:01:49.180 --> 00:01:51.400
of get it all off the ground.

00:01:51.400 --> 00:01:53.900
It went through a lot of
different incarnations

00:01:53.900 --> 00:01:56.360
to get to where it is today.

00:01:56.360 --> 00:01:58.250
Just a few years ago,

00:01:58.250 --> 00:02:01.200
it was only a few single
licenses being used

00:02:01.200 --> 00:02:04.560
by Congressional
Cartography Project

00:02:04.560 --> 00:02:07.140
and some analysts in CRS.

00:02:07.140 --> 00:02:11.440
Today, it is the geospatial
hosting environment.

00:02:11.440 --> 00:02:13.660
The geospatial hosting
environment is a series

00:02:13.660 --> 00:02:15.000
of portals.

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:18.220
We collect terabytes
of geospatial data.

00:02:18.220 --> 00:02:23.380
We have hundreds of users,
all of which come from either

00:02:23.380 --> 00:02:29.920
across the street, the Senate,
the House members, CRS analysts,

00:02:29.920 --> 00:02:31.720
geography and maps,

00:02:31.720 --> 00:02:35.060
Congressional Cartography
Project, and even curators

00:02:35.060 --> 00:02:37.560
with the new story maps project

00:02:37.560 --> 00:02:40.450
that we began publishing
collections and things

00:02:40.450 --> 00:02:42.170
like that here in the library.

00:02:42.170 --> 00:02:45.100
There are some people
in the crowd

00:02:45.100 --> 00:02:48.040
who have been responsible
for this growth.

00:02:48.040 --> 00:02:51.570
I see Mike Handy,
retired many years ago,

00:02:51.570 --> 00:02:54.450
was part of our IT team here,

00:02:54.450 --> 00:02:57.180
who is one of the most
responsible people

00:02:57.180 --> 00:03:00.120
for building what is the
geospatial hosting environment

00:03:00.120 --> 00:03:02.020
here at the library
and kind of pushing it

00:03:02.020 --> 00:03:04.250
through the sixth floor.

00:03:04.250 --> 00:03:07.200
We have our engineering
team in the back, Bebe,

00:03:07.200 --> 00:03:11.500
who was one of the research
and development heads,

00:03:11.500 --> 00:03:17.020
who worked this through during
the last few years, and then,

00:03:17.020 --> 00:03:20.250
we have our engineering
team, basically known

00:03:20.250 --> 00:03:23.100
as Butch and the Two Mikes.

00:03:23.100 --> 00:03:28.570
Yes, and they do have a band,
plays hits from Python and JSON.

00:03:28.570 --> 00:03:31.400
And that would be Butch
Lazerac [assumed spelling],

00:03:31.400 --> 00:03:33.600
Mike Scholen [assumed spelling],
who sitting back there,

00:03:33.600 --> 00:03:36.210
and Mike Bijou, who
was also in the back,

00:03:36.210 --> 00:03:39.190
all of whom played a
big role in getting GIS

00:03:39.190 --> 00:03:42.290
to where it is in the library.

00:03:42.290 --> 00:03:43.590
It's growing.

00:03:43.590 --> 00:03:45.680
It's growing rapidly.

00:03:45.680 --> 00:03:49.530
Our new chief, Paulette
Hasier, has been responsible

00:03:49.530 --> 00:03:53.630
for pushing the cloud-based
online story map program

00:03:53.630 --> 00:03:58.070
and moving that forward
at a sort of lightspeed.

00:03:58.070 --> 00:04:00.260
We've now published a
whole series of those.

00:04:00.260 --> 00:04:03.140
Curators across the
library are using them.

00:04:03.140 --> 00:04:06.100
There is training
being done, and so,

00:04:06.100 --> 00:04:09.090
the program is moving rapidly.

00:04:09.090 --> 00:04:12.940
But if it was just
data and software,

00:04:12.940 --> 00:04:15.140
it really wouldn't mean much.

00:04:15.140 --> 00:04:17.150
It's more than that.

00:04:17.150 --> 00:04:20.650
It's about getting the
staff in the Congress.

00:04:20.650 --> 00:04:23.020
It's about getting
the staff in CRS.

00:04:23.020 --> 00:04:26.040
It's about getting people
in GNM and curators all

00:04:26.040 --> 00:04:30.180
over the library to use their
imagination and creativity.

00:04:30.180 --> 00:04:34.300
To understand how to
use these tools in order

00:04:34.300 --> 00:04:39.760
to foster what their ideas are,
analysis, looking at things

00:04:39.760 --> 00:04:42.340
from a spatial perspective.

00:04:42.340 --> 00:04:46.610
And so, today, we're
going to settle on that.

00:04:46.610 --> 00:04:48.410
Spatial thinking.

00:04:48.410 --> 00:04:50.080
Spatial activity.

00:04:50.080 --> 00:04:52.220
What can it tell
us about the world?

00:04:52.220 --> 00:04:54.800
What can it tell us
about what we are?

00:04:54.800 --> 00:04:58.930
And so, these talks that we're
going to see today are going

00:04:58.930 --> 00:05:03.540
to focus on K-12 education,
and it's very important,

00:05:03.540 --> 00:05:06.460
because when we think
about GIS, when we think

00:05:06.460 --> 00:05:10.990
about where geography has come
as a discipline in the last 20

00:05:10.990 --> 00:05:13.980
to 30 years, it's gone
through a revolution,

00:05:13.980 --> 00:05:18.400
and that revolution has allowed
the field to begin to think

00:05:18.400 --> 00:05:21.350
of things in ways that
it never did before.

00:05:21.350 --> 00:05:24.230
It's allowed it to combine
humanistic thinking,

00:05:24.230 --> 00:05:27.550
critical thinking, with
scientific analysis.

00:05:27.550 --> 00:05:30.280
It's allowed it to come to terms

00:05:30.280 --> 00:05:34.080
with things the way human beings
interact with the environment,

00:05:34.080 --> 00:05:37.360
the way they interact
with themselves,

00:05:37.360 --> 00:05:40.470
with the way we interact with
each other in a spatial way.

00:05:40.470 --> 00:05:43.980
It's given us the tools
to begin thinking deeply

00:05:43.980 --> 00:05:47.900
about those problems and about
the way we live in society,

00:05:47.900 --> 00:05:50.380
and that's an extremely
important thing.

00:05:50.380 --> 00:05:54.260
To a certain extent, cartography
has always been about this.

00:05:54.260 --> 00:05:56.140
It's always been
about imagination.

00:05:56.140 --> 00:05:58.060
It's always been
about visualization.

00:05:58.060 --> 00:06:00.420
It's always been about
spatial thinking.

00:06:00.420 --> 00:06:02.730
One can think back to
the second century A.D.

00:06:02.730 --> 00:06:05.660
where Ptolemy is sitting
in Alexandria staring

00:06:05.660 --> 00:06:08.550
out at the Mediterranean Sea
trying to figure out a way

00:06:08.550 --> 00:06:12.000
in order to map the world,
to visualize the world.

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:15.450
We can think of Francois Menard,
the great French cartographer,

00:06:15.450 --> 00:06:18.530
who is sitting in his study
in Paris trying to figure

00:06:18.530 --> 00:06:23.970
out what can space add to my
analysis of transatlantic trade?

00:06:23.970 --> 00:06:25.370
How can I visualize this?

00:06:25.370 --> 00:06:27.900
And coming up with
radical ways of doing it.

00:06:27.900 --> 00:06:32.560
Or it can be a group of hipsters
sitting in a bar wondering how

00:06:32.560 --> 00:06:34.010
in God's name can we map

00:06:34.010 --> 00:06:36.950
in three dimensions
the lives of squirrels?

00:06:36.950 --> 00:06:40.560
So, it can be a lot of different
things, and all of those things

00:06:40.560 --> 00:06:42.930
that I've just said, the
squirrels, the Ptolemy,

00:06:42.930 --> 00:06:47.010
and the Menard, if you come to
the open house, you'll be able

00:06:47.010 --> 00:06:50.690
to see all of those maps,
because we selected those.

00:06:50.690 --> 00:06:54.600
And so, when we start
thinking about what GIS is,

00:06:54.600 --> 00:06:58.030
and we start thinking about
how we can influence people

00:06:58.030 --> 00:07:01.840
in K-12 education, and I
especially want to thank any

00:07:01.840 --> 00:07:05.190
of the teachers who are
here today, because it's

00:07:05.190 --> 00:07:07.770
in your hands that this is,

00:07:07.770 --> 00:07:11.740
that these developments
are going to be thrust.

00:07:11.740 --> 00:07:13.640
The kids coming up
today, the children coming

00:07:13.640 --> 00:07:19.320
up today are going to have tools
that can be used for good or,

00:07:19.320 --> 00:07:23.900
in fact, for not so good,
and getting them to use them

00:07:23.900 --> 00:07:26.760
for good, getting them to
understand the excitement

00:07:26.760 --> 00:07:30.460
of doing an analysis that might
squeeze a little bit more food

00:07:30.460 --> 00:07:35.790
yield out of the
landscape to feed people,

00:07:35.790 --> 00:07:40.380
to help people distribute
limited water resources,

00:07:40.380 --> 00:07:44.210
and to understand, well, maybe
even squirrels, is something

00:07:44.210 --> 00:07:48.050
that we can start with
very early and very simply.

00:07:48.050 --> 00:07:51.790
The data that we now have and
the tools that we now have,

00:07:51.790 --> 00:07:55.650
can be brought down to the
level of K-12 students in a way

00:07:55.650 --> 00:07:57.560
that we never could before.

00:07:57.560 --> 00:08:02.750
The excitement of a child
mapping a squirrel in a park,

00:08:02.750 --> 00:08:06.810
interacting with the data, the
computers, and with the world.

00:08:06.810 --> 00:08:12.690
It's that triangle that
K-12 builds in students,

00:08:12.690 --> 00:08:17.460
and is that triangle that's very
important, and is that triangle

00:08:17.460 --> 00:08:20.720
that we're going to
explore in our talks today.

00:08:20.720 --> 00:08:24.600
And so, I want to
bring up Tim St. Onge,

00:08:24.600 --> 00:08:27.790
who's going to be the host in
the introducer and the master

00:08:27.790 --> 00:08:29.980
of ceremonies for the
rest of the conference.

00:08:29.980 --> 00:08:32.200
And again, I want to
thank you for coming,

00:08:32.200 --> 00:08:34.040
and especially the teachers.

00:08:34.040 --> 00:08:35.340
We're here for you.

00:08:35.340 --> 00:08:37.140
Thanks.

