00:09:45.560 --> 00:09:49.690
&gt;&gt; Kathy Hart: All right,
well, happy GIS day.

00:09:49.690 --> 00:09:52.540
So, I am here, as you just
heard, I'm here to talk

00:09:52.540 --> 00:09:55.710
about spatial thinking,
but before I do that,

00:09:55.710 --> 00:09:58.950
I want to talk about maps.

00:09:58.950 --> 00:10:02.620
So, when was the last time that
you looked closely at a map?

00:10:02.620 --> 00:10:05.090
I mean, it really
dug in and read it

00:10:05.090 --> 00:10:08.890
to uncover the meaning behind
the lines, colors, and symbols.

00:10:08.890 --> 00:10:12.610
Did it all makes sense?

00:10:12.610 --> 00:10:15.170
Did you understand
the intent of the map?

00:10:15.170 --> 00:10:18.230
Did you examine the legend
and the text to help you

00:10:18.230 --> 00:10:21.370
with the overall
meaning of the map?

00:10:21.370 --> 00:10:23.290
Did you understand
the main concepts,

00:10:23.290 --> 00:10:25.640
the cartographer's intent?

00:10:25.640 --> 00:10:28.770
The same question can asked
regarding digital geographic

00:10:28.770 --> 00:10:30.760
maps, or GISs, as well.

00:10:30.760 --> 00:10:34.270
Did you move through those
locations, zoom in and out,

00:10:34.270 --> 00:10:37.610
understand the layers and
ability to select those layers

00:10:37.610 --> 00:10:39.660
that were of most
interest to you?

00:10:39.660 --> 00:10:40.960
Okay, so, great.

00:10:40.960 --> 00:10:42.910
You are a spatial thinker.

00:10:42.910 --> 00:10:46.680
So, I do want to talk
about how you make meaning

00:10:46.680 --> 00:10:48.210
from those lines, colors,

00:10:48.210 --> 00:10:50.980
and symbols on the
maps and GIS sites.

00:10:50.980 --> 00:10:53.520
What happens at the
cognitive level?

00:10:53.520 --> 00:10:56.030
And what can we do to
enhance the spatial thinking

00:10:56.030 --> 00:10:58.100
and spatial understanding
skills,

00:10:58.100 --> 00:11:01.900
including in the schools,
with our K-12 students.

00:11:01.900 --> 00:11:03.200
So, why do we care?

00:11:03.200 --> 00:11:04.930
Where we talk about this today?

00:11:04.930 --> 00:11:08.350
Well, spatial thinking underpins
the whole -- the map reading,

00:11:08.350 --> 00:11:10.990
the map interpretation,
map creation.

00:11:10.990 --> 00:11:14.370
It helps our K-12 students
succeed in their classes,

00:11:14.370 --> 00:11:16.330
as well as their careers.

00:11:16.330 --> 00:11:20.430
Spatial thinking correlates with
success in math and science,

00:11:20.430 --> 00:11:22.510
and as, therefore, students

00:11:22.510 --> 00:11:26.280
with strong spatial thinking
skills are adding advantage

00:11:26.280 --> 00:11:30.010
in their coursework and
their later career options.

00:11:30.010 --> 00:11:32.430
So, it follows that
instructional resources

00:11:32.430 --> 00:11:35.850
for spatial thinking are
critical in the early years.

00:11:35.850 --> 00:11:39.340
The good news is that there's
been a great deal of interest

00:11:39.340 --> 00:11:41.070
and research on spatial thinking

00:11:41.070 --> 00:11:43.820
and enhancing spatial-related
curriculum.

00:11:43.820 --> 00:11:46.160
Much of the research
includes a digital component,

00:11:46.160 --> 00:11:48.860
including teaching
GIS in schools.

00:11:48.860 --> 00:11:51.490
So, what I hope to do my time
this morning is to create

00:11:51.490 --> 00:11:54.020
for you the conceptual
connections

00:11:54.020 --> 00:11:57.840
between spatial thinking and
map reading and the use of maps

00:11:57.840 --> 00:11:59.950
and 3D models and learning GIS

00:11:59.950 --> 00:12:02.240
and related digital
environments.

00:12:02.240 --> 00:12:06.450
How these can expand a student's
spatial habits of mind,

00:12:06.450 --> 00:12:10.920
which then increases spatial
awareness and spatial skills.

00:12:10.920 --> 00:12:14.180
Beyond K-12, in our everyday
lives, it's important

00:12:14.180 --> 00:12:16.590
to think spatially,
in that it helps us

00:12:16.590 --> 00:12:17.890
to be informed citizens.

00:12:17.890 --> 00:12:24.770
So, a few fields of
studies and careers.

00:12:24.770 --> 00:12:26.900
These should be familiar to you.

00:12:26.900 --> 00:12:28.940
There's probably others
that I don't have listed,

00:12:28.940 --> 00:12:33.300
but this is just to kind of get
you thinking about the variety.

00:12:33.300 --> 00:12:36.940
So many things that are
touched by spatial thinking,

00:12:36.940 --> 00:12:40.170
as far as fields of
study and careers.

00:12:40.170 --> 00:12:44.480
And I'm sure there's some that
I missed, but you can fill

00:12:44.480 --> 00:12:46.950
in the blank on others.

00:12:46.950 --> 00:12:51.490
So, the types of spatial
relationships, it's important

00:12:51.490 --> 00:12:55.300
to understand the range from
the simple to the more complex,

00:12:55.300 --> 00:12:58.620
and it's important when
we're looking at maps in GIS

00:12:58.620 --> 00:13:01.160
to use precise terminology.

00:13:01.160 --> 00:13:04.570
So, we're talking about, you
know, where things are located,

00:13:04.570 --> 00:13:07.020
the distance between two things?

00:13:07.020 --> 00:13:08.320
Is there movement?

00:13:08.320 --> 00:13:10.290
Where are the boundaries?

00:13:10.290 --> 00:13:11.590
Is there a region?

00:13:11.590 --> 00:13:14.100
Is something adjacent
to something else?

00:13:14.100 --> 00:13:17.060
Is something enclosed or within?

00:13:17.060 --> 00:13:19.650
So again, these are terms that
when you're looking at maps

00:13:19.650 --> 00:13:21.990
and using GIS, these
are the kinds of things

00:13:21.990 --> 00:13:24.090
that you're trying to uncover.

00:13:24.090 --> 00:13:28.530
And then, you go into the more
complex spatial relationships.

00:13:28.530 --> 00:13:30.010
What are the patterns?

00:13:30.010 --> 00:13:32.080
How are things distributed?

00:13:32.080 --> 00:13:33.380
Are there dispersion?

00:13:33.380 --> 00:13:37.040
Is there clustering involved?

00:13:37.040 --> 00:13:39.810
So, as you look at maps in
GIS again, these are the types

00:13:39.810 --> 00:13:41.710
of things you're
trying to understand.

00:13:41.710 --> 00:13:45.680
At the younger ages, at the very
of the stages, children come

00:13:45.680 --> 00:13:48.870
to understand the basic
topological spatial concepts,

00:13:48.870 --> 00:13:53.310
such as on, and, with,
close to, next to,

00:13:53.310 --> 00:13:55.440
beside, over and inside.

00:13:55.440 --> 00:13:59.890
They understand these
just in everyday life

00:13:59.890 --> 00:14:04.620
and when they're
learning their vocabulary.

00:14:04.620 --> 00:14:07.940
At around 6 to 8 years
old, children progress

00:14:07.940 --> 00:14:10.780
to more complex,
projective understanding,

00:14:10.780 --> 00:14:17.500
such as in front of, left of,
right of, on the side, behind,

00:14:17.500 --> 00:14:21.460
straight, and up the
hill and down the hill.

00:14:21.460 --> 00:14:25.880
And this image that you're
looking at here is just kind

00:14:25.880 --> 00:14:27.780
of a way to understand
with those concepts mean

00:14:27.780 --> 00:14:29.400
when you're looking at a map.

00:14:29.400 --> 00:14:31.310
So, were talking
about verbal as well

00:14:31.310 --> 00:14:34.860
as visual skills,
spatial skills.

00:14:34.860 --> 00:14:37.210
But it's not all work.

00:14:37.210 --> 00:14:39.230
There's also play involved.

00:14:39.230 --> 00:14:41.200
And while most children pick

00:14:41.200 --> 00:14:44.310
up these concepts
naturally, some do struggle.

00:14:44.310 --> 00:14:48.120
But it comes, as I mentioned, it
comes informally in daily life,

00:14:48.120 --> 00:14:50.600
as part of the acquisition
of vocabulary,

00:14:50.600 --> 00:14:53.670
as well as more formally
in classroom activities

00:14:53.670 --> 00:14:55.040
and focused curriculum.

00:14:55.040 --> 00:14:57.830
But think about the
common toys at this age.

00:14:57.830 --> 00:15:00.620
Much of the playtime
involves spatial thinking.

00:15:00.620 --> 00:15:01.980
So, you have building blocks.

00:15:01.980 --> 00:15:03.280
You have cars and trucks.

00:15:03.280 --> 00:15:06.070
You have doll houses,
Legos, and Rubik's Cubes.

00:15:06.070 --> 00:15:08.250
These objects can be arranged

00:15:08.250 --> 00:15:12.400
and rearranged using the
child's native spatial awareness

00:15:12.400 --> 00:15:15.900
and the inborn creativity.

00:15:15.900 --> 00:15:18.750
Numerous digital games
also use spatial abilities.

00:15:18.750 --> 00:15:23.110
Minecraft is one that comes to
mind, but there are many others.

00:15:23.110 --> 00:15:26.990
So, this is all, again, in
the kind of younger ages,

00:15:26.990 --> 00:15:31.210
but around grades five and
six, the more abstract,

00:15:31.210 --> 00:15:35.160
or the Euclidean understandings
emerge, as does curriculum,

00:15:35.160 --> 00:15:39.080
on using a frame of reference,
such as how to measure distances

00:15:39.080 --> 00:15:42.470
and direction and using
a coordinate system.

00:15:42.470 --> 00:15:45.410
So, how many of you have
seen these maps, right?

00:15:45.410 --> 00:15:51.590
So, the children are asked to
make a map of a place they know.

00:15:51.590 --> 00:15:53.670
Basically, how you
get from school,

00:15:53.670 --> 00:15:55.530
from your home to school?

00:15:55.530 --> 00:15:58.670
And so, this is really
good practice,

00:15:58.670 --> 00:16:01.920
because some elementary-age
children may have difficulty

00:16:01.920 --> 00:16:03.260
understanding maps.

00:16:03.260 --> 00:16:04.560
So, practice.

00:16:04.560 --> 00:16:08.350
That practice with things they
know is a very important point

00:16:08.350 --> 00:16:11.350
for them to kind of
bring that understanding.

00:16:11.350 --> 00:16:15.870
So, their drawings, their maps,
typically include their house.

00:16:15.870 --> 00:16:18.920
Maybe a curvy line
representing the street

00:16:18.920 --> 00:16:22.550
and the school building,
and it's not to scale.

00:16:22.550 --> 00:16:25.880
The perspective and the
angle or vantage point is

00:16:25.880 --> 00:16:27.720
from an on-the-ground
perspective,

00:16:27.720 --> 00:16:29.590
so street view rather than from

00:16:29.590 --> 00:16:32.330
above as we know
typical used maps.

00:16:32.330 --> 00:16:34.470
The children understand
one key aspect

00:16:34.470 --> 00:16:35.950
of map reading and map creation.

00:16:35.950 --> 00:16:37.760
That's self-location.

00:16:37.760 --> 00:16:40.950
So, the self-location is the
ability to relate where you are

00:16:40.950 --> 00:16:44.290
in the real world to
a place on the map,

00:16:44.290 --> 00:16:47.750
and they do that by
drawing and viewing it.

00:16:47.750 --> 00:16:50.700
So, these two examples
show some fairly complex

00:16:50.700 --> 00:16:53.950
and sophisticated
thinking going on.

00:16:53.950 --> 00:16:56.490
They also show two
other spatial abilities.

00:16:56.490 --> 00:16:59.590
That's route memory
and map rotation.

00:16:59.590 --> 00:17:02.590
Route memory is the
ability to remember a way to

00:17:02.590 --> 00:17:06.290
and from a place, and map
rotation is the ability

00:17:06.290 --> 00:17:08.880
to mentally rotate a map
while you are making turns

00:17:08.880 --> 00:17:11.040
without physically
turning a map.

00:17:11.040 --> 00:17:12.920
So, you don't have
to raise your hand

00:17:12.920 --> 00:17:15.180
if you actually still do
the turning of the map.

00:17:15.180 --> 00:17:17.060
It's okay.

00:17:17.060 --> 00:17:19.730
We can work on that.

00:17:19.730 --> 00:17:23.140
But these two maps illustrate
all these concepts really well,

00:17:23.140 --> 00:17:29.730
and you know, kudos to the
students that created these.

00:17:29.730 --> 00:17:35.910
Now I don't know the gender of
these two who created these,

00:17:35.910 --> 00:17:39.680
and if there's any teachers in
the room, you may have an idea.

00:17:39.680 --> 00:17:42.250
May be the one on the left might
be a girl, and maybe the one

00:17:42.250 --> 00:17:43.550
on the right might be a boy.

00:17:43.550 --> 00:17:45.930
And I want to bring that up,

00:17:45.930 --> 00:17:49.240
because there are
some sex differences.

00:17:49.240 --> 00:17:51.850
There's studies that show
that males perform better,

00:17:51.850 --> 00:17:55.080
slightly better, on
spatial tests such as

00:17:55.080 --> 00:18:00.070
with mental rotation tasks and
wayfinding, and explanations

00:18:00.070 --> 00:18:02.550
as to the reason for
these differences very,

00:18:02.550 --> 00:18:05.080
and some relate to the
environment in the home.

00:18:05.080 --> 00:18:07.010
For instance, in one study,

00:18:07.010 --> 00:18:09.480
there were no gender
differences found in children

00:18:09.480 --> 00:18:11.770
from lower income homes.

00:18:11.770 --> 00:18:15.510
However, there were gender
differences found in children

00:18:15.510 --> 00:18:18.780
from the middle and
higher-income groups.

00:18:18.780 --> 00:18:22.830
So, I will give you a second to
think about why that might be.

00:18:24.370 --> 00:18:28.200
So, it may be due to their
home environment, right?

00:18:28.200 --> 00:18:30.600
So, I'm happy, though, to report

00:18:30.600 --> 00:18:33.650
that whatever differences
there may be due to biology

00:18:33.650 --> 00:18:37.220
or individual differences
or economic circumstances,

00:18:37.220 --> 00:18:39.360
these are easily
remedied by instruction

00:18:39.360 --> 00:18:42.980
and increasing access to
spatial-related activities.

00:18:42.980 --> 00:18:46.950
So, my message to parents and
grandparents, give your girls

00:18:46.950 --> 00:18:50.370
and kids Legos, building blocks.

00:18:50.370 --> 00:18:53.510
Teachers, encourage all
of your students to engage

00:18:53.510 --> 00:18:57.640
in spatial play activities in
the classroom, especially those

00:18:57.640 --> 00:19:02.110
who may not have the
opportunity at home.

00:19:02.110 --> 00:19:06.340
So, moving a little bit more
into the map reading in GIS,

00:19:06.340 --> 00:19:08.960
there's a lot of standard
methods that have been developed

00:19:08.960 --> 00:19:12.010
over the years, so,
with map design,

00:19:12.010 --> 00:19:14.750
and that really helps everyone.

00:19:14.750 --> 00:19:16.930
So that when we go
to read something,

00:19:16.930 --> 00:19:20.980
we have a common
vocabulary, common language.

00:19:20.980 --> 00:19:25.010
And Jacques Bertin developed
frameworks, or visual variables,

00:19:25.010 --> 00:19:29.390
as guides to map design,
and these are the concepts,

00:19:29.390 --> 00:19:34.360
which I hope you can see in the
back, of position, size, shape,

00:19:34.360 --> 00:19:39.260
the value or likeness, the
color or hue, and orientation,

00:19:39.260 --> 00:19:42.250
which may be called
direction, and texture,

00:19:42.250 --> 00:19:44.040
so as you can see in this chart.

00:19:44.040 --> 00:19:48.950
So, these concepts extend to
GIS, as well, and I just point

00:19:48.950 --> 00:19:51.490
out Access Map prepared
this particular chart,

00:19:51.490 --> 00:19:55.000
and there's a lot of description
on their website, as well.

00:19:55.000 --> 00:19:59.590
So, the point is, when you're
reading a map or creating a GIS,

00:19:59.590 --> 00:20:02.790
it's important to understand
the theoretical background

00:20:02.790 --> 00:20:06.040
and sometimes complexity
to the symbology.

00:20:06.040 --> 00:20:10.050
This is just a small part
to a much larger topic.

00:20:10.050 --> 00:20:16.070
And I should also point out that
these concepts can be combined.

00:20:16.070 --> 00:20:20.450
So, you may have color and shape
that are combined, and you know,

00:20:20.450 --> 00:20:22.620
we understand that when
we're looking at maps,

00:20:22.620 --> 00:20:26.890
and this applies to
points, lines, and polygons.

00:20:26.890 --> 00:20:29.490
So again, these are kind
of the building blocks

00:20:29.490 --> 00:20:33.060
to how we put maps together.

00:20:33.060 --> 00:20:36.190
And as I mentioned earlier,
the spatial thinking,

00:20:36.190 --> 00:20:38.290
it's a combination
of cognitive skills,

00:20:38.290 --> 00:20:41.010
comprised of knowing
concepts of space,

00:20:41.010 --> 00:20:42.750
using tools of representation

00:20:42.750 --> 00:20:45.320
and applying processes
of reasoning.

00:20:45.320 --> 00:20:48.380
What we're seeing
now, a recent study,

00:20:48.380 --> 00:20:51.190
that suggests a correlation
between thinking spatially

00:20:51.190 --> 00:20:52.830
and thinking geographically,

00:20:52.830 --> 00:20:56.200
and I will just read off this
section from this article

00:20:56.200 --> 00:20:58.270
from Metoyer and Bednarz.

00:20:58.270 --> 00:21:00.840
"Geographic thinking
extrapolates beyond spatial

00:21:00.840 --> 00:21:03.840
thinking to encompass the
recognition and elaboration

00:21:03.840 --> 00:21:06.510
of the relations
amongst spatial concepts,

00:21:06.510 --> 00:21:09.910
the advanced associations
derived from these concepts,

00:21:09.910 --> 00:21:12.230
and the formal linking
of the associations

00:21:12.230 --> 00:21:14.590
into theories and
generalizations."

00:21:14.590 --> 00:21:17.030
So, again, spatial thinking
is the building block.

00:21:17.030 --> 00:21:19.700
You add the geographic
concepts, and then you get

00:21:19.700 --> 00:21:21.450
into the geographic thinking.

00:21:21.450 --> 00:21:23.750
So again, maps in GIS.

00:21:24.810 --> 00:21:27.620
And when we talk about
geography, you're going

00:21:27.620 --> 00:21:31.080
into the geographic
realm, I hope some of you,

00:21:31.080 --> 00:21:32.380
if not maybe all of you,

00:21:32.380 --> 00:21:35.340
are aware of Tobler's
first law of geography.

00:21:35.340 --> 00:21:38.230
Everything is related
to everything else,

00:21:38.230 --> 00:21:41.190
but near things are more
related than distant things.

00:21:41.190 --> 00:21:42.910
So, think about that.

00:21:42.910 --> 00:21:45.500
How does that --
what does that mean?

00:21:45.500 --> 00:21:47.940
So, things are nearby.

00:21:47.940 --> 00:21:49.240
They're somewhat dependent.

00:21:49.240 --> 00:21:52.570
So, you have tree species that
are more similar to the trees

00:21:52.570 --> 00:21:55.750
that are in their
neighborhood then maybe trees

00:21:55.750 --> 00:21:58.800
across the country or on another
continent, another climate.

00:21:58.800 --> 00:22:04.900
Any kind of species,
animals, plants,

00:22:04.900 --> 00:22:07.890
but also demographic
and social issues.

00:22:07.890 --> 00:22:10.860
There you have similarities
in things that are near.

00:22:10.860 --> 00:22:13.370
You have more similarity
to things

00:22:13.370 --> 00:22:15.140
that are near, rather
than far away.

00:22:15.140 --> 00:22:16.790
So, we can keep that
in mind, also,

00:22:16.790 --> 00:22:18.290
when you're looking
at maps in GIS.

00:22:18.290 --> 00:22:20.460
What's going on in
that place as compared

00:22:20.460 --> 00:22:23.950
to what's going on farther away?

00:22:23.950 --> 00:22:26.540
And getting into why, again,

00:22:26.540 --> 00:22:28.420
why is geographic
thinking important?

00:22:28.420 --> 00:22:32.250
It's important because then
we have the whys of where.

00:22:32.250 --> 00:22:33.930
Where things happen is critical

00:22:33.930 --> 00:22:36.010
to knowing how and
why they happen.

00:22:36.010 --> 00:22:37.610
So, we want to study maps.

00:22:37.610 --> 00:22:41.340
GIS, we want to study geographic
concepts and do studies,

00:22:41.340 --> 00:22:44.830
because then we will know how
and why things are happening.

00:22:44.830 --> 00:22:49.010
We can plan, and we can
do all sorts of analyses

00:22:49.010 --> 00:22:52.230
and really understand our
world in a much better way.

00:22:52.230 --> 00:22:53.710
So, I want to circle back

00:22:53.710 --> 00:22:55.680
to what I mentioned
at the beginning.

00:22:55.680 --> 00:22:58.620
We know that spatial thinking
is very important for success

00:22:58.620 --> 00:23:01.660
in STEM, and we understand
that skills are based both

00:23:01.660 --> 00:23:05.430
on innate abilities, as well
as environmental inputs.

00:23:05.430 --> 00:23:06.760
So, it follows that we must look

00:23:06.760 --> 00:23:09.190
at the important
role of teachers.

00:23:09.190 --> 00:23:12.690
The skills of STEM and
non-STEM teachers are important,

00:23:12.690 --> 00:23:15.520
and it's not surprising
that studies have found

00:23:15.520 --> 00:23:19.470
that secondary STEM teachers
have strong spatial skills,

00:23:19.470 --> 00:23:22.950
as compared to non-STEM teachers
in the general population,

00:23:22.950 --> 00:23:24.790
as well as when compared
to preschool

00:23:24.790 --> 00:23:26.600
and primary school teachers.

00:23:26.600 --> 00:23:29.710
So, what this means is that our
high school chemistry, physics,

00:23:29.710 --> 00:23:34.670
and calculus teachers are much
stronger in spatial thinking.

00:23:34.670 --> 00:23:36.360
Obviously, that's a good thing.

00:23:36.360 --> 00:23:40.280
However, since spatial skill
development is formative

00:23:40.280 --> 00:23:43.220
in the primary school
years, we are reliant

00:23:43.220 --> 00:23:46.130
on our primary school teachers'
spatial skills to foster

00:23:46.130 --> 00:23:49.870
that strong spatial skills
and the younger ages.

00:23:49.870 --> 00:23:51.630
Workshops and professional
development

00:23:51.630 --> 00:23:53.780
for the primary school
teachers has been shown

00:23:53.780 --> 00:23:56.660
to increase their
confidence and abilities

00:23:56.660 --> 00:23:58.900
to teach spatial content.

00:23:58.900 --> 00:24:03.190
And I will point you to a few
articles, these first two.

00:24:03.190 --> 00:24:08.030
Nora Newcombe, who wrote
in American Educator,

00:24:08.030 --> 00:24:10.930
really has a great
introduction to this topic.

00:24:10.930 --> 00:24:12.610
And then, Learning
to Think Spatially;

00:24:12.610 --> 00:24:16.110
GIS as a Support System
in the K-12 Curriculum

00:24:16.110 --> 00:24:18.070
from the National
Research Council.

00:24:18.070 --> 00:24:21.210
That's a very robust
and in-depth report.

00:24:21.210 --> 00:24:23.600
I also encourage
you to read that.

00:24:23.600 --> 00:24:26.070
So, I hope by the established
the whys and where fors

00:24:26.070 --> 00:24:28.740
of spatial thinking, but
what does this have to do

00:24:28.740 --> 00:24:30.760
with libraries, you may ask?

00:24:30.760 --> 00:24:32.730
Well, let me tell you.

00:24:32.730 --> 00:24:37.440
Librarians are partnering
with K-12 educators

00:24:37.440 --> 00:24:40.300
to develop geographic
and spatial curriculum.

00:24:40.300 --> 00:24:44.470
I have the third and fourth
articles here are examples

00:24:44.470 --> 00:24:45.770
of that.

00:24:45.770 --> 00:24:49.110
In Colorado, Theobald
and Vrbancic have engaged

00:24:49.110 --> 00:24:52.980
with K-12 educators and school
librarians with great success,

00:24:52.980 --> 00:24:54.980
as well as in Florida.

00:24:54.980 --> 00:24:58.230
McAuliffe using aerial
photos in the University

00:24:58.230 --> 00:25:00.700
of Florida library,
partnered with teachers,

00:25:00.700 --> 00:25:02.920
to enhance the national
geography standards,

00:25:02.920 --> 00:25:05.060
Geography for Life.

00:25:05.060 --> 00:25:07.990
So, libraries are engaged
in information resources

00:25:07.990 --> 00:25:11.160
and information literacy
of all formats.

00:25:11.160 --> 00:25:14.480
And maps and GIS are among those
reliant on spatial thinking.

00:25:14.480 --> 00:25:16.150
So, it's incumbent upon us

00:25:16.150 --> 00:25:19.570
to develop geospatial
information literacy programs.

00:25:19.570 --> 00:25:22.220
So, stay tuned, as they say.

00:25:22.220 --> 00:25:23.720
So, as I wind down,

00:25:23.720 --> 00:25:26.470
I will encourage you
to think spatially.

00:25:26.470 --> 00:25:30.430
Observe spatial relationships
in your everyday life.

00:25:30.430 --> 00:25:32.290
Think critically about maps

00:25:32.290 --> 00:25:34.890
and the information
that they convey.

00:25:34.890 --> 00:25:39.230
Use precise terminology to
describe spatial phenomenon,

00:25:39.230 --> 00:25:40.530
and bring these concepts

00:25:40.530 --> 00:25:43.970
