00:30:13.890 --> 00:30:19.730
for the Geospatial Data Act
and your efforts in really,

00:30:19.730 --> 00:30:24.530
not just in lobbying for the
bill and contacting members

00:30:24.530 --> 00:30:26.920
and trying to get it
to pass, but the work

00:30:26.920 --> 00:30:29.710
that we all did coming to
agreement on what should be

00:30:29.710 --> 00:30:32.570
in the bill, and I say
thank you to everyone

00:30:32.570 --> 00:30:35.440
who participated in that.

00:30:35.440 --> 00:30:39.080
As was mentioned when I was
introduced, my background is

00:30:39.080 --> 00:30:40.550
in engineering and forestry.

00:30:40.550 --> 00:30:42.010
So, it's two areas

00:30:42.010 --> 00:30:46.420
where geospatial data is
used quite extensively,

00:30:46.420 --> 00:30:50.550
but I was thinking about
my engineering background,

00:30:50.550 --> 00:30:55.640
and I was partner in a
consulting engineering firm,

00:30:55.640 --> 00:30:59.610
and you know, we had to have
standards in our business.

00:30:59.610 --> 00:31:01.990
Like many businesses that want

00:31:01.990 --> 00:31:05.350
to be successful,
it makes good sense.

00:31:05.350 --> 00:31:09.080
It makes your business work more
efficiently and more effectively

00:31:09.080 --> 00:31:11.600
if you have good standards.

00:31:11.600 --> 00:31:13.940
We have standards
and specifications.

00:31:13.940 --> 00:31:16.630
We have certain things
that we knew were going

00:31:16.630 --> 00:31:20.440
to be purchased many times over.

00:31:20.440 --> 00:31:21.830
It wasn't rocket science.

00:31:21.830 --> 00:31:23.130
We'd gone through the design.

00:31:23.130 --> 00:31:27.820
We'd gone through the analysis,
and we could write standards

00:31:27.820 --> 00:31:30.350
and standard specifications.

00:31:30.350 --> 00:31:34.430
So that when it came
time to use the services

00:31:34.430 --> 00:31:40.060
or these materials again on the
job, that was all taken care of.

00:31:40.060 --> 00:31:43.340
And in our drawings,
you know, I'm old enough

00:31:43.340 --> 00:31:45.580
that I learned drafting
in college doing it

00:31:45.580 --> 00:31:47.960
with -- on a drawing board.

00:31:47.960 --> 00:31:51.880
And it's amazing things you
learn when you're doing it

00:31:51.880 --> 00:31:56.260
by hand that actually translate
into doing it digitally.

00:31:56.260 --> 00:31:59.870
You know, when you're
drawing on paper,

00:31:59.870 --> 00:32:03.690
you change your line weight
by using a different pencil.

00:32:03.690 --> 00:32:06.800
You do it by the amount
of pressure you put on it,

00:32:06.800 --> 00:32:09.190
and we had to have
standards even

00:32:09.190 --> 00:32:11.140
when we were drawing by hand.

00:32:11.140 --> 00:32:13.690
Really, it was almost more
important when we were drawing

00:32:13.690 --> 00:32:17.140
by hand, because it was so
time-consuming and laborious

00:32:17.140 --> 00:32:22.170
to make a drawing, that you
wanted to have certain drawings

00:32:22.170 --> 00:32:24.540
that you could use
over and over.

00:32:24.540 --> 00:32:28.570
It's just a little example
of what standardization does

00:32:28.570 --> 00:32:31.720
to make things work
more efficiently.

00:32:31.720 --> 00:32:34.970
We, as you all know, have an
issue in the federal government

00:32:34.970 --> 00:32:37.110
where we were being
very duplicative.

00:32:37.110 --> 00:32:39.700
We had different agencies
using different standards,

00:32:39.700 --> 00:32:45.270
different platforms and
formats, and there was a lot

00:32:45.270 --> 00:32:49.420
of taxpayer dollars going
to produce geospatial data

00:32:49.420 --> 00:32:53.600
that wasn't being --
or wasn't in a way

00:32:53.600 --> 00:32:56.810
that it could easily be
shared among agencies,

00:32:56.810 --> 00:33:00.210
and I'm not sure the agencies
were even communicating to know,

00:33:00.210 --> 00:33:02.030
you know, if one
agency had this data

00:33:02.030 --> 00:33:04.810
that another agency
could possibly use.

00:33:04.810 --> 00:33:08.780
So, that was the driver
behind doing this bill.

00:33:08.780 --> 00:33:10.080
I was fortunate.

00:33:10.080 --> 00:33:15.040
We got a very strong geospatial
data program in Arkansas.

00:33:15.040 --> 00:33:16.830
the state director of
that, Shelby Johnson,

00:33:16.830 --> 00:33:19.870
has been a longtime
friend of mine back

00:33:19.870 --> 00:33:21.720
when I was just doing
engineering work,

00:33:21.720 --> 00:33:23.210
before I ever got into politics.

00:33:23.210 --> 00:33:27.330
I worked with Shelby at
the -- they called it CAST,

00:33:27.330 --> 00:33:30.540
the Center for Advanced Spatial
Technologies at the University

00:33:30.540 --> 00:33:35.280
of Arkansas, where my
undergraduate degree is from

00:33:35.280 --> 00:33:41.340
and worked with Shelby there
and learned more and more

00:33:41.340 --> 00:33:43.520
about geospatial data systems.

00:33:43.520 --> 00:33:46.940
I went to forestry school
at Yale about the time

00:33:46.940 --> 00:33:49.120
when foresters were
really starting

00:33:49.120 --> 00:33:53.670
to use satellite imagery and
remote-sensing technologies,

00:33:53.670 --> 00:33:57.450
and the amount of time that
you can save, and really,

00:33:57.450 --> 00:33:59.450
the ceiling is still
way up there

00:33:59.450 --> 00:34:02.530
on the advancements we can make
an understanding our natural

00:34:02.530 --> 00:34:05.620
environment using
remote-sensing technologies.

00:34:05.620 --> 00:34:10.830
But I got to kind of come in
in the early stages of that

00:34:10.830 --> 00:34:17.270
and was able to use
that in my business

00:34:17.270 --> 00:34:18.960
to make better decisions

00:34:18.960 --> 00:34:20.860
and help the clients
that we were serving.

00:34:20.860 --> 00:34:24.890
So, I've kind of got a
working knowledge of GIS

00:34:24.890 --> 00:34:27.810
and the many ways that
it affects our lives,

00:34:27.810 --> 00:34:31.550
much more than what was used
in my engineering business,

00:34:31.550 --> 00:34:35.190
and I know that the way
technology is advancing

00:34:35.190 --> 00:34:40.430
that remote-sensing and GIS
and spatial data is going

00:34:40.430 --> 00:34:44.480
to be a more and more
important part of our lives.

00:34:44.480 --> 00:34:49.600
I know that is an engineer, if I
went into an existing facility,

00:34:49.600 --> 00:34:53.850
and we wanted to make
modernization to that facility,

00:34:53.850 --> 00:34:57.620
we would spend days, if not
weeks, taking hand measurements,

00:34:57.620 --> 00:35:00.960
making sketches, going back
and putting those sketches

00:35:00.960 --> 00:35:04.740
into a drawing, so that we would
know what was there before we

00:35:04.740 --> 00:35:06.040
got started.

00:35:06.040 --> 00:35:09.130
I'm sure, and this is
what happens when you get

00:35:09.130 --> 00:35:13.440
into Congress, you kind of get
out of touch with the details

00:35:13.440 --> 00:35:17.010
that you used to like
to stay so close to,

00:35:17.010 --> 00:35:20.580
but I know there were
sensing technologies

00:35:20.580 --> 00:35:24.910
where you could go inside
an existing facility using

00:35:24.910 --> 00:35:30.030
something like LIDAR and
measure everything in there

00:35:30.030 --> 00:35:33.410
from different places and put
it all together in a 3D drawing,

00:35:33.410 --> 00:35:36.590
and you can probably do that
very cost-effectively now,

00:35:36.590 --> 00:35:38.890
and some of you may know
all about how to do that,

00:35:38.890 --> 00:35:42.220
but there's just, like I
said, the sky's the limit

00:35:42.220 --> 00:35:48.620
on where we can go with
geospatial data, and this bill,

00:35:48.620 --> 00:35:53.350
I think, is a very good
start in getting standards

00:35:53.350 --> 00:35:54.650
across the federal government,

00:35:54.650 --> 00:35:57.710
which will probably affect
many things outside the

00:35:57.710 --> 00:35:59.010
federal government.

00:35:59.010 --> 00:36:01.400
I've got to say thank
you to Senator Hatch,

00:36:01.400 --> 00:36:04.790
who was the Senate sponsor
on this bill and work so hard

00:36:04.790 --> 00:36:11.160
to get it included
in the FAA bill.

00:36:11.160 --> 00:36:13.870
When I'm on the Transportation
and Infrastructure Committee,

00:36:13.870 --> 00:36:16.480
I'm on the Aviation
Subcommittee,

00:36:16.480 --> 00:36:19.970
and had you asked me
this time last year

00:36:19.970 --> 00:36:23.620
about getting the
geospatial data act as part

00:36:23.620 --> 00:36:26.860
of the FAA bill, I would've
just given you a strange look,

00:36:26.860 --> 00:36:31.630
but that's kind of the
way things happened here.

00:36:31.630 --> 00:36:36.130
And I'm excited about where
the future will take us.

00:36:36.130 --> 00:36:41.490
As you all know, what this bill
did was basically codified some

00:36:41.490 --> 00:36:49.490
things in the -- that the
OMB had already put out,

00:36:49.490 --> 00:36:54.670
codified the Federal
Geographic Data Committee

00:36:54.670 --> 00:36:59.120
and also codified the National
Geospatial Advisory Committee.

00:36:59.120 --> 00:37:04.400
It defined the geospatial
data infrastructure.

00:37:04.400 --> 00:37:06.750
It talks about data
themes, and from there,

00:37:06.750 --> 00:37:08.620
how to develop standards.

00:37:08.620 --> 00:37:13.170
It talks about geoplatform,
and then,

00:37:13.170 --> 00:37:16.820
it gets into the covered
agency responsibilities.

00:37:16.820 --> 00:37:20.820
One of the hurdles we had
to get through and this was

00:37:20.820 --> 00:37:26.990
with the Defense Department
and intelligence groups.

00:37:26.990 --> 00:37:29.030
They didn't necessarily
want to share their data

00:37:29.030 --> 00:37:31.230
across platforms, which
is understandable.

00:37:31.230 --> 00:37:34.620
So, we carved out exemptions
for them, but the rest

00:37:34.620 --> 00:37:39.550
of our agencies, hopefully,
as we move forward,

00:37:39.550 --> 00:37:43.970
we'll see much easier, seamless
transition between sharing data

00:37:43.970 --> 00:37:46.310
across agencies, and I'm
hoping that the oversight

00:37:46.310 --> 00:37:50.550
that we established in this bill
will get more agencies talking

00:37:50.550 --> 00:37:52.090
and sharing data and also making

00:37:52.090 --> 00:37:54.710
that data more available
for the public.

00:37:54.710 --> 00:37:58.940
So, we don't get to celebrate
that often Washington DC

00:37:58.940 --> 00:38:03.750
about a big win like this,
but this really is a big win

00:38:03.750 --> 00:38:05.450
that happened in
an unexpected way.

00:38:05.450 --> 00:38:07.870
And again, I want to say
thank you for all the work

00:38:07.870 --> 00:38:11.180
that you put into it, it is
just an honor for me to get

00:38:11.180 --> 00:38:17.170
to be part of it, and you
know, this isn't going to be --

00:38:17.170 --> 00:38:21.350
people actually not even heard
of the Geospatial Data Act.

00:38:21.350 --> 00:38:25.230
They just know we passed
in FAA bill, and you know,

00:38:25.230 --> 00:38:27.060
I go home to my constituents,
and they say,

00:38:27.060 --> 00:38:28.360
"Well, what have you done?"

00:38:28.360 --> 00:38:30.790
And I say, well, we got this
Geospatial Data Act passed,

00:38:30.790 --> 00:38:32.290
and they look at me like,

00:38:32.290 --> 00:38:34.070
that's what we elected
you to Congress to do?

00:38:34.070 --> 00:38:37.850
I say, well, it actually
affects a lot of your life.

00:38:37.850 --> 00:38:41.030
I said, if you use one of
those smartphones you got.

00:38:41.030 --> 00:38:42.440
You pull up a map program.

00:38:42.440 --> 00:38:44.420
I say, that's geospatial data.

00:38:44.420 --> 00:38:46.830
I said, the weather that you
look at every day, I said,

00:38:46.830 --> 00:38:48.170
there's just tons of ways

00:38:48.170 --> 00:38:52.160
that geospatial data affects
your life, and we did something

00:38:52.160 --> 00:38:55.380
to streamline that process and
make it more user friendly,

00:38:55.380 --> 00:38:58.300
and hopefully, make life
better for more Americans.

00:38:58.300 --> 00:39:01.920
It's not the sexiest thing in
the world, but I'm glad to be,

00:39:01.920 --> 00:39:06.650
as a fellow nerd, I'm glad to
be part of the cause, and again,

00:39:06.650 --> 00:39:08.850
appreciate your support.

