maps and get real creative,

00:44:54.150 --> 00:44:57.190
and I know that technology's
increased even more.

00:44:57.190 --> 00:45:01.600
So yeah, it'll definitely
be used in census data.

00:45:03.040 --> 00:45:06.120
&gt;&gt; Female: So, you mentioned
the disparity between standards

00:45:06.120 --> 00:45:11.740
and what was being published in
the geospatial data environment.

00:45:11.740 --> 00:45:14.760
You talked a little bit about
your background as an engineer

00:45:14.760 --> 00:45:16.980
and also, the importance
in forestry,

00:45:16.980 --> 00:45:19.940
but why was this bill
so important to you?

00:45:19.940 --> 00:45:21.520
Why did you champion it?

00:45:21.520 --> 00:45:22.820
&gt;&gt; Congressman Bruce
Westerman: Well,

00:45:22.820 --> 00:45:25.930
I like to see things work
efficiently and effectively,

00:45:25.930 --> 00:45:29.180
and I understand the
importance of standards

00:45:29.180 --> 00:45:35.450
and common platforms, and I've
seen the success in Arkansas

00:45:35.450 --> 00:45:41.730
with our GIS departments there
and the leadership, really,

00:45:41.730 --> 00:45:43.500
that Shelby's been
able to bring to that,

00:45:43.500 --> 00:45:46.630
and I just thought there was
a better way to do government

00:45:46.630 --> 00:45:51.480
at the federal level, and
this is a good governance bill

00:45:51.480 --> 00:45:54.520
that should save
taxpayers dollars

00:45:54.520 --> 00:45:55.910
and provide a better service.

00:45:55.910 --> 00:46:00.660
So, it was easy for me to
get on board to support it.

00:46:00.660 --> 00:46:08.100
I wish we could find more pieces
of legislation like this.'

00:46:08.100 --> 00:46:09.520
&gt;&gt; Male: So, [speaking
off mic] your final point.

00:46:09.520 --> 00:46:12.000
I'm just curious if,
sort of looking ahead,

00:46:12.000 --> 00:46:14.790
if there are more types of bills
or more types of initiatives

00:46:14.790 --> 00:46:17.150
that you might need
jumping onto that,

00:46:17.150 --> 00:46:19.830
that might relate
more efficiently

00:46:19.830 --> 00:46:22.500
to geospatial education

00:46:22.500 --> 00:46:25.000
or for promoting geospatial
technology development

00:46:25.000 --> 00:46:27.500
in the government or beyond?

00:46:27.500 --> 00:46:29.340
&gt;&gt; Congressman Bruce Westerman:
Yeah, and I think we need

00:46:29.340 --> 00:46:31.920
to give this piece
of legislation time

00:46:31.920 --> 00:46:34.200
to get implemented, and
there will always be tweaks

00:46:34.200 --> 00:46:35.750
that need to be made.

00:46:35.750 --> 00:46:38.840
I'm also a huge proponent
of STEM education,

00:46:38.840 --> 00:46:42.850
which geospatial data
education would fall

00:46:42.850 --> 00:46:44.510
in that stem category.

00:46:44.510 --> 00:46:52.000
You know, I have four children,
one still in high school,

00:46:52.000 --> 00:46:58.170
and they all got a little bit
of exposure to geospatial data

00:46:58.170 --> 00:47:03.120
in a program called EAST, that
actually originated in Arkansas,

00:47:03.120 --> 00:47:07.530
and I see programs like
than continuing to grow,

00:47:07.530 --> 00:47:11.110
and it's amazing when the
interest it can create

00:47:11.110 --> 00:47:14.430
in young people, who may have
never thought about a career

00:47:14.430 --> 00:47:16.840
in STEM, when they
get to start playing

00:47:16.840 --> 00:47:19.730
around with satellite
data and remote sensing

00:47:19.730 --> 00:47:22.690
and building their own maps
and doing projects with that.

00:47:22.690 --> 00:47:28.230
So, I think it will -- I think
the educational component will

00:47:28.230 --> 00:47:32.000
come along to support the
science in the industry.

