&gt;&gt; Female: What's
the timeline expected

00:47:39.650 --> 00:47:48.100
for getting all the government
agencies on the same page,

00:47:48.100 --> 00:47:49.400
as far as the standards go?

00:47:49.400 --> 00:47:50.700
[speaking off mic]

00:47:50.700 --> 00:47:52.000
&gt;&gt; Congressman Bruce
Westerman: I don't know

00:47:52.000 --> 00:47:53.870
if an official timeline has been
established yet, but you know,

00:47:53.870 --> 00:47:56.440
my response to the agencies
would be you're not done yet.

00:47:56.440 --> 00:47:58.440
You know? And you all know
-- and this is a hard thing.

00:47:58.440 --> 00:48:03.180
You know, we have huge
issues in the world today

00:48:03.180 --> 00:48:07.070
with cybersecurity, which
GIS also can play a part

00:48:07.070 --> 00:48:14.340
in cybersecurity, but one
problem with trying to legislate

00:48:14.340 --> 00:48:17.570
and regulate anything that
has to do with technology,

00:48:17.570 --> 00:48:19.840
and especially with
computer systems,

00:48:19.840 --> 00:48:25.480
is that by the time government
gets the big massive slow

00:48:25.480 --> 00:48:29.590
machinery moving and just
momentum, everything's changed.

00:48:29.590 --> 00:48:31.660
So, it's got to be
something is responsive.

00:48:31.660 --> 00:48:34.930
That's why hope that
these two committees

00:48:34.930 --> 00:48:39.890
that have been codified
will work closely together

00:48:39.890 --> 00:48:44.650
to monitor the situation and to
build something that can react

00:48:44.650 --> 00:48:48.190
at the same speed that
technology changes today,

00:48:48.190 --> 00:48:51.820
if that's at all possible
in the federal government.

00:48:51.820 --> 00:48:54.010
I think that's a huge challenge,

00:48:54.010 --> 00:48:58.390
and we all know how slow
the federal government moves

00:48:58.390 --> 00:48:59.690
on things.

00:48:59.690 --> 00:49:03.520
But this is one that
it really needs

00:49:03.520 --> 00:49:07.440
to have a bigger
flame built under it,

00:49:07.440 --> 00:49:09.090
I guess, to move faster.

00:49:09.090 --> 00:49:12.660
And that's one thing that I will
keep pushing for, is following

00:49:12.660 --> 00:49:15.630
up with, you know,
most of this is --

00:49:15.630 --> 00:49:17.720
falls under the Department
of Interior.

00:49:17.720 --> 00:49:19.780
So, we have a lot of
contacts over there

00:49:19.780 --> 00:49:23.060
that we'll be following up with
to say where you at on this?

00:49:23.060 --> 00:49:24.980
How can we help?

00:49:24.980 --> 00:49:28.530
And, you know, what's your
timeline kind of thing?

00:49:28.530 --> 00:49:31.380
But I think you all can
help with that, too.

00:49:31.380 --> 00:49:35.360
Just because we've got a bill
signed into law doesn't mean

00:49:35.360 --> 00:49:37.990
that anything's happened to it.

00:49:37.990 --> 00:49:41.910
We've got to get
the code written

00:49:41.910 --> 00:49:45.250
and get the agencies
to implement the law.

00:49:49.050 --> 00:49:51.150
Well, again, thank
you for your time,

00:49:51.150 --> 00:49:54.560
and I can't say enough
how humbled I am to get

00:49:54.560 --> 00:50:00.200
to be the person that got to
carry this piece of legislation.

00:50:00.200 --> 00:50:05.470
We'll make nerds proud
everywhere, and it's really,

00:50:05.470 --> 00:50:10.980
really -- I can't express
enough how much your work

00:50:10.980 --> 00:50:13.050
and efforts helped
to get this done.

00:50:13.050 --> 00:50:16.210
Without your work and
efforts, we wouldn't get

00:50:16.210 --> 00:50:18.330
to celebrate today
the fact that we got

00:50:18.330 --> 00:50:20.870
to the geospatial data
act signed into law.

00:50:20.870 --> 00:50:24.170
So again, thank you, and
