I'm not going to lie.

00:51:54.470 --> 00:51:57.210
But I'm really excited to
be here, in particular,

00:51:57.210 --> 00:52:00.880
because the focus today is
on GIS in K-12 education,

00:52:00.880 --> 00:52:03.530
and that's what our
GeoMentors Program is all about.

00:52:03.530 --> 00:52:06.310
The GeoMentors Programs is a
nationwide network of volunteers

00:52:06.310 --> 00:52:07.610
who are looking to do.

00:52:07.610 --> 00:52:10.680
Find ways to insert GIS and
geography in spatial thinking,

00:52:10.680 --> 00:52:12.740
any way we can, into
K-12 classrooms

00:52:12.740 --> 00:52:15.100
and student groups
across the country.

00:52:15.100 --> 00:52:18.870
So, that's what I'll
be talking about today.

00:52:18.870 --> 00:52:21.020
So, the AAG is partnered
with Esri

00:52:21.020 --> 00:52:23.530
for the GeoMentors Programs,
and this was borne out of,

00:52:23.530 --> 00:52:25.840
starting in 2015, for
the GeoMentors Program,

00:52:25.840 --> 00:52:28.870
Esri made a fantastic
donation saying, hey,

00:52:28.870 --> 00:52:30.260
we've got this software
platform.

00:52:30.260 --> 00:52:32.650
We will give it to any K-12
school the US that wants it

00:52:32.650 --> 00:52:34.840
and wants to use it, which
is fantastic, and even now,

00:52:34.840 --> 00:52:37.780
they've expanded that donation,
and Charlie, who'll speak

00:52:37.780 --> 00:52:39.660
after me, will have a lot
more to say about this,

00:52:39.660 --> 00:52:40.960
but now it's also available

00:52:40.960 --> 00:52:43.220
to all K-12 schools
internationally, as well.

00:52:43.220 --> 00:52:44.550
So, this is fantastic, right?

00:52:44.550 --> 00:52:48.070
Students have the opportunity to
map with the same software that,

00:52:48.070 --> 00:52:49.370
you know, industry
and government

00:52:49.370 --> 00:52:51.640
and business were using around
the world, which is great.

00:52:51.640 --> 00:52:53.880
But we can't always just, of
course, just take software

00:52:53.880 --> 00:52:57.110
and drop it in the laps of K-12
schools, because they have tons

00:52:57.110 --> 00:53:00.560
of time, right, to learn
new technology or find a way

00:53:00.560 --> 00:53:02.070
to insert this in curriculum.

00:53:02.070 --> 00:53:04.770
No, so, you know, as we had the
foresight of thinking, yeah,

00:53:04.770 --> 00:53:06.440
this is a great gift, but
we know it's not going

00:53:06.440 --> 00:53:08.740
to be the easiest
thing to implement.

00:53:08.740 --> 00:53:11.760
So, with the free software
bundle, let's also bundle

00:53:11.760 --> 00:53:13.720
in some free help,
and that's the idea

00:53:13.720 --> 00:53:15.300
of having this GeoMentors
network.

00:53:15.300 --> 00:53:18.670
Volunteers who will work with
a teacher, with the classroom,

00:53:18.670 --> 00:53:21.030
with a school district, asking
them what they would like to do

00:53:21.030 --> 00:53:22.910
with this technology,
kind of teaching them

00:53:22.910 --> 00:53:24.210
about the technology,

00:53:24.210 --> 00:53:25.510
and helping them implement
it in the classroom.

00:53:25.510 --> 00:53:26.810
So, there's the best chance

00:53:26.810 --> 00:53:30.040
for the software give
to actually get used.

00:53:30.040 --> 00:53:32.560
Our current GeoMentors
network, as of yesterday,

00:53:32.560 --> 00:53:35.830
was 1814 people who
have signed up.

00:53:35.830 --> 00:53:38.240
So, every dot on this map is
someone who is, basically,

00:53:38.240 --> 00:53:39.710
another Geo nerd,
who was like, yeah,

00:53:39.710 --> 00:53:41.660
I want to help get kids mapping.

00:53:41.660 --> 00:53:42.960
Who doesn't?

00:53:42.960 --> 00:53:44.260
So, they're available.

00:53:44.260 --> 00:53:45.560
This is an interactive map.

00:53:45.560 --> 00:53:47.330
So, any teachers in the
room, you can go on here,

00:53:47.330 --> 00:53:48.720
click on this, learn
about people,

00:53:48.720 --> 00:53:50.020
find their contact information.

00:53:50.020 --> 00:53:51.320
We also have a database.

00:53:51.320 --> 00:53:52.620
So, you can search keywords.

00:53:52.620 --> 00:53:53.920
You can have certain
topics you're teaching.

00:53:53.920 --> 00:53:55.710
These are all people who
are interested, are ready,

00:53:55.710 --> 00:53:58.740
and willing to work with a
teacher or with a youth group

00:53:58.740 --> 00:54:00.860
or something like that.

00:54:00.860 --> 00:54:04.280
So, teachers, again, see these
points as resources for you

00:54:04.280 --> 00:54:05.890
and those of you
potential GeoMentors,

00:54:05.890 --> 00:54:07.960
consider adding your
dot to the map.

00:54:07.960 --> 00:54:10.670
So, this is a lot of volunteers,
which is great, but if you think

00:54:10.670 --> 00:54:12.980
of how many schools and
classrooms there are to reach,

00:54:12.980 --> 00:54:18.100
we could always use a few more
good people helping us out.

00:54:18.100 --> 00:54:19.960
So, then your next
thought might be, well,

00:54:19.960 --> 00:54:21.260
who can be a GeoMentor?

00:54:21.260 --> 00:54:23.880
I run into so many people
thinking, can I be a GeoMentor?

00:54:23.880 --> 00:54:26.340
If you're asking yourself,
if you're here on GIS Day,

00:54:26.340 --> 00:54:28.150
if you know what GIS day is,

00:54:28.150 --> 00:54:30.810
you're already super
qualified to be a GeoMentor.

00:54:30.810 --> 00:54:33.160
And I'm not saying that
it's because, you know,

00:54:33.160 --> 00:54:34.760
you don't have to
be an absolute whiz.

00:54:34.760 --> 00:54:36.060
You're not going to
go into a classroom

00:54:36.060 --> 00:54:37.360
and they expect you to, yeah,

00:54:37.360 --> 00:54:39.040
I need you to Python
program to do this.

00:54:39.040 --> 00:54:40.450
No, right?

00:54:40.450 --> 00:54:42.890
So, I have a lot of people who
get intimidated and realize

00:54:42.890 --> 00:54:44.190
and think I can't do it.

00:54:44.190 --> 00:54:45.750
You have so much more
to offer than you think.

00:54:45.750 --> 00:54:48.020
If you know what GIS is, if
you know the cool web map

00:54:48.020 --> 00:54:50.140
and can lead a class
through asking questions

00:54:50.140 --> 00:54:54.360
that can be answered spatially
by looking at imagery or,

00:54:54.360 --> 00:54:55.870
you know, adding
different data layers.

00:54:55.870 --> 00:54:57.360
That's being a great GeoMentor.

00:54:57.360 --> 00:54:59.750
So, if you're here.

00:54:59.750 --> 00:55:03.000
It's more the enthusiasm of
the passion that's a perquisite

00:55:03.000 --> 00:55:05.680
than a certain type
or level of skills.

00:55:05.680 --> 00:55:07.370
So, we're not just academics.

00:55:07.370 --> 00:55:08.670
We're not just GISPs.

00:55:08.670 --> 00:55:10.260
We're not just geographers.

00:55:10.260 --> 00:55:12.010
So, it's anyone from undergrads.

00:55:12.010 --> 00:55:15.040
They're some of our most
enthusiastic volunteers.

00:55:15.040 --> 00:55:16.660
To retirees and everyone
in between,

00:55:16.660 --> 00:55:19.900
from all different
disciplines, are our GeoMentors.

00:55:19.900 --> 00:55:21.200
So, don't be intimidated

00:55:21.200 --> 00:55:23.730
and think you don't know
enough to be a volunteer.

00:55:23.730 --> 00:55:27.520
And you can really see the
diversity of our volunteers

00:55:27.520 --> 00:55:29.650
