So, with younger kids, we do
have GeoMentors who will just go

01:05:06.520 --> 01:05:08.550
in sometimes with
a giant wall map.

01:05:08.550 --> 01:05:10.580
National Geographic has
those huge floor maps

01:05:10.580 --> 01:05:11.950
of the states that
are fantastic.

01:05:11.950 --> 01:05:14.020
So, kids will run around in
socks, hopping around on,

01:05:14.020 --> 01:05:16.040
you know, cities
and mountain ranges.

01:05:16.040 --> 01:05:19.750
Bottom left, actually, it's an
undergraduate geography society

01:05:19.750 --> 01:05:22.490
at a university partners with
a local high school and takes

01:05:22.490 --> 01:05:23.800
over the classroom
for a couple days

01:05:23.800 --> 01:05:26.230
to teach high schoolers
with ArcGIS online.

01:05:26.230 --> 01:05:30.080
In the center there, working
with the AP GIS class,

01:05:30.080 --> 01:05:31.380
making custom web maps.

01:05:31.380 --> 01:05:34.140
Can you imagine getting to do
that at the high school level?

01:05:34.140 --> 01:05:36.950
I started learning
GIS when I was 24,

01:05:36.950 --> 01:05:39.630
and I felt young starting at 24.

01:05:39.630 --> 01:05:42.480
But when I think of just a
different way of thinking

01:05:42.480 --> 01:05:44.680
and the future of the field
and innovation that will come

01:05:44.680 --> 01:05:47.040
from students intuitively
knowing how to work

01:05:47.040 --> 01:05:51.320
with this stuff at a younger
and younger age, it's exciting.

01:05:51.320 --> 01:05:54.220
Top right, working with a
Girls Innovation Academy.

01:05:54.220 --> 01:05:55.520
Again, that sounds supercool.

01:05:55.520 --> 01:05:57.780
I want to go back in time
and be in these things,

01:05:57.780 --> 01:06:00.600
but teaching geo referencing
and wetlands mapping.

01:06:00.600 --> 01:06:04.020
And the bottom one, an example,
again, of working at a distance.

01:06:04.020 --> 01:06:07.550
So, Rob Spacecraft, he actually
puts that on his name badges

01:06:07.550 --> 01:06:11.230
at conferences, Spacecraft
as to go by.

01:06:11.230 --> 01:06:12.530
Fun with names.

01:06:12.530 --> 01:06:13.830
Puns with names.

01:06:13.830 --> 01:06:15.690
But he virtually mentored
students in California,

01:06:15.690 --> 01:06:17.930
who were working on story map
submissions for a contest.

01:06:17.930 --> 01:06:20.350
So, wasn't even in the same
place, but could go back

01:06:20.350 --> 01:06:22.230
and forth and advise
them, help them find data,

01:06:22.230 --> 01:06:25.130
and that sort of thing.

01:06:25.130 --> 01:06:26.430
And I'll just keep sharing more.

01:06:26.430 --> 01:06:28.030
So, this picture,
top left to Justin.

01:06:28.030 --> 01:06:29.750
He's the one who had a paper
map with the younger kids,

01:06:29.750 --> 01:06:31.670
but now you see him
teaching, you know,

01:06:31.670 --> 01:06:33.410
digital mapping with
an older crowd.

01:06:33.410 --> 01:06:35.530
So, adapting with the students
or with what's available

01:06:35.530 --> 01:06:36.830
in the classroom, right?

01:06:36.830 --> 01:06:38.130
You just have to adapt.

01:06:38.130 --> 01:06:40.330
So, this is a very good
exercise in adapting.

01:06:40.330 --> 01:06:42.100
Top right, Annette

01:06:42.100 --> 01:06:44.480
in Pennsylvania does
amazing jobs working

01:06:44.480 --> 01:06:45.780
with all these different schools

01:06:45.780 --> 01:06:49.030
and getting just the
most adorable, you know,

01:06:49.030 --> 01:06:50.910
activities of kids going
out and doing surveying

01:06:50.910 --> 01:06:55.660
and collecting data in
the field, and of course,

01:06:55.660 --> 01:06:57.460
can you spot the
geospatial professional

01:06:57.460 --> 01:06:59.390
in a sea of fourth-graders?

01:06:59.390 --> 01:07:01.560
I'll give you a moment.

01:07:01.560 --> 01:07:05.710
And maybe it's because he or
she, you know, is really blended

01:07:05.710 --> 01:07:07.720
in there, or maybe it's because
the fourth-graders are looking

01:07:07.720 --> 01:07:09.520
more and more like
geospatial professionals.

01:07:09.520 --> 01:07:10.820
I don't know.

01:07:10.820 --> 01:07:14.770
I'll leave that is
food for thought.

01:07:14.770 --> 01:07:17.700
And really, the other
thing is, this also,

01:07:17.700 --> 01:07:20.250
it's not just one directional
of GeoMentors are out going

01:07:20.250 --> 01:07:22.940
and doing a thing and just
students are benefiting.

01:07:22.940 --> 01:07:25.150
I really found that
everyone kind of benefits,

01:07:25.150 --> 01:07:27.280
and you don't necessarily
predict

01:07:27.280 --> 01:07:29.190
which way the geomentoring
really is going to happen.

01:07:29.190 --> 01:07:33.020
So, I don't know if you see
our tiny man-big vest here

01:07:33.020 --> 01:07:34.320
in the front left, right?

01:07:34.320 --> 01:07:37.620
That's Oliver, and Oliver is the
son of his geomentor dad next

01:07:37.620 --> 01:07:41.390
to him, and when his geomentor
dad goes and does drone exhibits

01:07:41.390 --> 01:07:44.530
and kind of demonstrations for
classrooms, Oliver goes with him

01:07:44.530 --> 01:07:45.870
and is super jazzed about it.

01:07:45.870 --> 01:07:47.170
He likes to help.

01:07:47.170 --> 01:07:48.470
He likes to be the helper.

01:07:48.470 --> 01:07:50.060
So, while I know
there's a classroom

01:07:50.060 --> 01:07:52.390
of students here learning about
drones, I think there's a lot

01:07:52.390 --> 01:07:54.930
of geomentoring here
between Oliver and his dad,

01:07:54.930 --> 01:07:56.890
and we've got a geomentor
in training here.

01:07:56.890 --> 01:07:59.510
And he's learning about what his
dad does and what's interesting

01:07:59.510 --> 01:08:00.810
about this, and he's learning

01:08:00.810 --> 01:08:02.410
about teaching other
students, as well.

01:08:02.410 --> 01:08:06.050
So, there's a lot of
positive, multidirectional kind

01:08:06.050 --> 01:08:09.340
of benefits out of these
geomentoring opportunities.

01:08:10.470 --> 01:08:13.720
So, maybe I have some of
you hooked thinking, I mean,

01:08:13.720 --> 01:08:15.800
maybe I could do that possibly.

01:08:15.800 --> 01:08:18.470
So, how do you get involved?

01:08:18.470 --> 01:08:19.770
It's painless.

01:08:19.770 --> 01:08:21.070
I promise.

01:08:21.070 --> 01:08:22.990
You just sign up online,
and you're not obligated

01:08:22.990 --> 01:08:25.190
to anything, assigned
anything, required anything.

01:08:25.190 --> 01:08:26.970
You just get in our
communication loop.

01:08:26.970 --> 01:08:28.270
So, you'll get emails.

01:08:28.270 --> 01:08:30.930
He'll get newsletters, and
you'll be a dot on the map.

01:08:30.930 --> 01:08:33.700
So, educators and schools can
find you and reach out to you.

01:08:33.700 --> 01:08:36.300
If there are educators in
the room, and you would

01:08:36.300 --> 01:08:38.350
like to also put
your name out there

01:08:38.350 --> 01:08:39.860
and saying, hey, I want help.

01:08:39.860 --> 01:08:41.960
We have a sign up for
educators, as well.

01:08:41.960 --> 01:08:44.200
So, if you sign up, then
GeoMentors will be notified,

01:08:44.200 --> 01:08:46.730
and they can contact you, and
you can say what you're looking

01:08:46.730 --> 01:08:48.840
for and what kind
of help you want.

01:08:48.840 --> 01:08:51.350
And once you've signed up, and
if you're ready at some point,

01:08:51.350 --> 01:08:53.560
and I will say, we ask
GeoMentors to get involved

01:08:53.560 --> 01:08:55.710
when they can to the
extent that they can.

01:08:55.710 --> 01:08:57.310
Maybe it's a one-time thing.

01:08:57.310 --> 01:08:59.380
Maybe it's an ongoing
collaboration for a semester,

01:08:59.380 --> 01:09:02.150
or a year, or beyond, but
every little bit helps.

01:09:02.150 --> 01:09:04.760
So, I don't think I only
have this much time.

01:09:04.760 --> 01:09:07.030
So, I can't do it, or
that kind of thing.

01:09:07.030 --> 01:09:09.100
We don't have any limitations
or anything like that.

01:09:09.100 --> 01:09:11.840
Again, every little bit helps to
be the spark for the educator,

01:09:11.840 --> 01:09:13.870
the spark for the
student, a spark for you.

01:09:13.870 --> 01:09:15.990
So, connecting with
a collaborator,

01:09:15.990 --> 01:09:18.370
I will be straightforward,
it's not always the easiest

01:09:18.370 --> 01:09:20.220
to make roads into
the K-12 communities.

01:09:20.220 --> 01:09:21.910
Charlie knows a lot
more about that.

01:09:21.910 --> 01:09:24.400
So, sometimes this can be
the most challenging thing.

01:09:24.400 --> 01:09:27.840
As a GeoMentor, you can, first
of all, see what educators are

01:09:27.840 --> 01:09:29.140
out there requesting help.

01:09:29.140 --> 01:09:30.860
We do tend to have more
volunteers putting their name

01:09:30.860 --> 01:09:32.660
on the map then educators.

01:09:32.660 --> 01:09:35.510
Contact local schools
in your area.

01:09:35.510 --> 01:09:38.160
You can see which schools have
signed up for the software

01:09:38.160 --> 01:09:39.460
and which ones haven't.

01:09:39.460 --> 01:09:41.060
So, that's a strategy of
go to schools that have

01:09:41.060 --> 01:09:43.790
or approach schools that
haven't and tell them about it,

01:09:43.790 --> 01:09:45.420
if you want to do that
kind of advocacy angle.

01:09:45.420 --> 01:09:47.420
You can also work
with youth groups,

01:09:47.420 --> 01:09:49.820
because they're also
eligible to get free software.

01:09:49.820 --> 01:09:52.200
So, maybe you've volunteered
with Boy Scouts or Girl Scouts

01:09:52.200 --> 01:09:54.660
or 4-H or Boys and
Girls Clubs of America.

01:09:54.660 --> 01:09:57.940
Those are options too, or
afterschool clubs affiliated

01:09:57.940 --> 01:09:59.580
with schools, as well.

01:09:59.580 --> 01:10:01.010
So, think outside the box.

01:10:01.010 --> 01:10:02.820
What are environments
that students are

01:10:02.820 --> 01:10:04.250
in that I could work with?

01:10:04.250 --> 01:10:06.190
But we really encourage
people to work

01:10:06.190 --> 01:10:08.420
through your social network.

01:10:08.420 --> 01:10:11.630
Most people have a connection
to K-12 in their life, right?

01:10:11.630 --> 01:10:13.300
So, it's their kids' school.

01:10:13.300 --> 01:10:14.600
Their friend is a teacher.

01:10:14.600 --> 01:10:15.900
Their alma mater, right?

01:10:15.900 --> 01:10:17.200
So, think of it that way.

01:10:17.200 --> 01:10:19.080
One, it makes little bit easier.

01:10:19.080 --> 01:10:21.220
People know who you are
and why you want to help,

01:10:21.220 --> 01:10:23.180
because you're just
invested, and you're kind

01:10:23.180 --> 01:10:24.480
of more invested,
too, because you know

01:10:24.480 --> 01:10:25.780
who you're helping already.

01:10:25.780 --> 01:10:28.620
But you could be the
person that brings GIS

01:10:28.620 --> 01:10:29.920
to your elementary
school, right?

01:10:29.920 --> 01:10:31.790
So, your middle school
to your high school.

01:10:31.790 --> 01:10:33.550
Again, a lot of parents
who are working

01:10:33.550 --> 01:10:34.890
with their own kids' teachers.

01:10:34.890 --> 01:10:36.590
Some of them follow
them through the grades.

01:10:36.590 --> 01:10:39.100
So, they'll work with the grade
level that their child is at,

01:10:39.100 --> 01:10:40.400
and they're going and adapting.

01:10:40.400 --> 01:10:41.700
And so, they're starting
with elementary.

01:10:41.700 --> 01:10:44.180
Now they're in middle and
adapting their skills,

01:10:44.180 --> 01:10:46.670
as well, with doing that.

01:10:46.670 --> 01:10:48.830
And again, for those who
are seeking a GeoMentor,

01:10:48.830 --> 01:10:50.130
the online map is there,

01:10:50.130 --> 01:10:51.960
but there's also a
database, as well.

01:10:51.960 --> 01:10:54.930
So, you can connect and
find people that way.

01:10:54.930 --> 01:10:56.360
And we don't just say, woo-hoo!

01:10:56.360 --> 01:11:01.330
Sign up! We try and put as much
resources as we can in one spot

01:11:01.330 --> 01:11:02.630
to have more than enough
to get you started.

01:11:02.630 --> 01:11:04.680
So, if you go to our website,
you know, we have information

01:11:04.680 --> 01:11:05.980
on how to find people.

01:11:05.980 --> 01:11:07.280
How to talk to them.

01:11:07.280 --> 01:11:08.580
Also, how to connect
with each other.

01:11:08.580 --> 01:11:09.880
We do want this to
be a community.

01:11:09.880 --> 01:11:11.180
So, we have online communities.

01:11:11.180 --> 01:11:12.480
We have social media.

01:11:12.480 --> 01:11:14.190
How you can share
your story, and also,

01:11:14.190 --> 01:11:16.350
a review other people's
stories, as well.

01:11:16.350 --> 01:11:19.720
And you can gain service and
outreach experience, which,

01:11:19.720 --> 01:11:22.120
in and of itself, is
fulfilling, but some people,

01:11:22.120 --> 01:11:24.510
particularly undergrads who are
looking to have more experience,

01:11:24.510 --> 01:11:27.480
if you tell us about your story,
which we really want you to do,

01:11:27.480 --> 01:11:29.620
we'll document it and
give you a certificate,

01:11:29.620 --> 01:11:31.980
and anyone who is an
aspiring GISP, right,

01:11:31.980 --> 01:11:36.160
this can work towards your
accreditation or your renewal.

01:11:36.160 --> 01:11:38.370
And I mentioned the
case studies.

01:11:38.370 --> 01:11:39.950
This is how you can
really find out more

01:11:39.950 --> 01:11:42.350
about these variety
of experiences.

01:11:42.350 --> 01:11:44.670
We have over 40 case studies
from 27 different states,

01:11:44.670 --> 01:11:46.800
and these are people who
took the time to write a lot

01:11:46.800 --> 01:11:48.160
about their experience.

01:11:48.160 --> 01:11:49.960
How did they find someone?

01:11:49.960 --> 01:11:51.690
You know, how much
time did it take?

01:11:51.690 --> 01:11:52.990
That's something
we want to know.

01:11:52.990 --> 01:11:54.290
What did they teach?

01:11:54.290 --> 01:11:55.590
What worked well?

01:11:55.590 --> 01:11:56.890
What didn't work well?

01:11:56.890 --> 01:11:58.190
And what did they
learn from experience?

01:11:58.190 --> 01:11:59.490
How was it for them?

01:11:59.490 --> 01:12:01.720
So, I encourage you to go
online and check those out,

01:12:01.720 --> 01:12:03.390
and what we really
hear is, again,

01:12:03.390 --> 01:12:05.040
how much our volunteers
get out of it.

01:12:05.040 --> 01:12:06.340
All right?

01:12:06.340 --> 01:12:07.640
So, it's invigorating to
have students show enthusiasm

01:12:07.640 --> 01:12:09.500
in what each of us have
chosen as a career.

01:12:09.500 --> 01:12:12.090
Or as Diana said, "It encouraged
me in my day-to-day work.

01:12:12.090 --> 01:12:14.980
It reminded me of how fun GIS
can be and how it can be applied

01:12:14.980 --> 01:12:16.280
to almost everything
you do daily."

01:12:16.280 --> 01:12:19.020
I think sometimes we forget
that, oh, yeah, this is fun.

01:12:19.020 --> 01:12:21.050
Right? Oh, yeah, you can
use this for a lot more

01:12:21.050 --> 01:12:23.240
than just what I do
in my discipline here.

01:12:23.240 --> 01:12:26.300
So, I think this can actually
be really reinvigorating

01:12:26.300 --> 01:12:28.040
for our volunteers, as well.

01:12:28.040 --> 01:12:31.150
So, I encourage you, if
you're not signed up,

01:12:31.150 --> 01:12:33.720
if you'd like to sign up or
at least check us out online,

01:12:33.720 --> 01:12:36.830
reach out to us on Twitter,
email, and all that,

01:12:36.830 --> 01:12:38.130
and I want to thank you again

01:12:38.130 --> 01:12:41.510
for having me here
today and happy GIS Day.

