01:14:50.230 --> 01:14:53.300
and were comfortable with
them and had time to mess

01:14:53.300 --> 01:14:55.110
around with them, and
there was no curriculum.

01:14:55.110 --> 01:14:59.230
And so, ArcView 1 was out.

01:14:59.230 --> 01:15:03.050
And then ArcView 2, and by the
time that ArcView 3 was around,

01:15:03.050 --> 01:15:04.800
there were things
that people could do.

01:15:04.800 --> 01:15:06.100
There were some activities.

01:15:06.100 --> 01:15:10.130
There were some projects,
and really, it was projects

01:15:10.130 --> 01:15:12.540
that made it happen for people.

01:15:12.540 --> 01:15:15.350
Getting people to say,
hey, there's a thing

01:15:15.350 --> 01:15:17.190
that I really want to explore,

01:15:17.190 --> 01:15:21.680
and that's been the
watchword all the way through,

01:15:21.680 --> 01:15:24.300
whether it's I want to take
a look at the watershed

01:15:24.300 --> 01:15:26.710
in my community, or I
want to see the world

01:15:26.710 --> 01:15:28.830
in several different
projections,

01:15:28.830 --> 01:15:33.260
or I have this battle that I
really like to think about.

01:15:33.260 --> 01:15:37.950
There's something that people
want to do in their class

01:15:37.950 --> 01:15:40.060
and have the time and
have the passion to do,

01:15:40.060 --> 01:15:43.050
but it was really the
oddball way back then.

01:15:43.050 --> 01:15:48.700
Then about 2000, things
started to roll fast.

01:15:48.700 --> 01:15:52.120
We came out with this GIS
in schools, but with a set

01:15:52.120 --> 01:15:54.230
of case studies of
what people are doing

01:15:54.230 --> 01:15:55.910
and some best practices.

01:15:55.910 --> 01:15:59.810
And 2002 was a real
watershed, because we came

01:15:59.810 --> 01:16:02.390
out with this big green
book, Mapping our World.

01:16:02.390 --> 01:16:06.680
And that was a curriculum where
there was the software in place,

01:16:06.680 --> 01:16:10.510
and there were activities
for world geography

01:16:10.510 --> 01:16:12.500
that people could go through,
and they were doing it

01:16:12.500 --> 01:16:14.550
from third and fourth
grade on up

01:16:14.550 --> 01:16:19.460
into grad school using
that one resource.

01:16:19.460 --> 01:16:23.550
And they been doing that
over the years with ArcView 3

01:16:23.550 --> 01:16:26.220
and then ArcView 9
and then ArcView 10

01:16:26.220 --> 01:16:28.800
and then ArcGIS online.

01:16:28.800 --> 01:16:31.510
That resource has
been fairly timeless,

01:16:31.510 --> 01:16:35.020
but what also happened
back in 2000 was

01:16:35.020 --> 01:16:36.320
that kids started appearing

01:16:36.320 --> 01:16:39.150
up on the Esri user
conference stage,

01:16:39.150 --> 01:16:41.090
and you can see in the top left.

01:16:41.090 --> 01:16:43.220
There's a group that
is sitting on top

01:16:43.220 --> 01:16:45.020
of this thing called
the geography network,

01:16:45.020 --> 01:16:48.940
which was starting to get
to be online capacity,

01:16:48.940 --> 01:16:51.330
and they were actually
some of the first users

01:16:51.330 --> 01:16:53.320
of the geography network.

01:16:53.320 --> 01:16:55.500
They were working with
some data from online.

01:16:55.500 --> 01:16:57.670
So, this was something
that was, you know,

01:16:57.670 --> 01:17:00.350
presaging the big
change that was coming.

01:17:00.350 --> 01:17:03.140
The group in the top right,
they look like little munchkins.

01:17:03.140 --> 01:17:06.870
They were fourth-graders who
came up on stage and were able

01:17:06.870 --> 01:17:09.940
to prove to people what
it is that kids can do,

01:17:09.940 --> 01:17:14.160
because these guys said, hey,
Department of Natural Resources,

01:17:14.160 --> 01:17:18.020
your model about what these
toads, with these tiny,

01:17:18.020 --> 01:17:21.670
little horny toads in
central Washington,

01:17:21.670 --> 01:17:24.480
that they only travel of
thousand feet in their life,

01:17:24.480 --> 01:17:25.870
but the ones that
we're tracking,

01:17:25.870 --> 01:17:27.770
they've traveled three,
four times that much.

01:17:27.770 --> 01:17:29.070
So, your models are wrong.

01:17:29.070 --> 01:17:30.400
So, go fix them.

01:17:30.400 --> 01:17:33.170
And so, that was really
important for people to get

01:17:33.170 --> 01:17:35.590
to see that students
can do a lot.

01:17:35.590 --> 01:17:39.170
So then came these,
you know, that whole --

01:17:39.170 --> 01:17:41.090
this world that you
see in the center came

01:17:41.090 --> 01:17:43.770
out with the mapping
our world book,

01:17:43.770 --> 01:17:46.670
and it was a powerful
thing for people to see.

01:17:46.670 --> 01:17:49.570
That this is what GIS people do.

01:17:49.570 --> 01:17:53.440
This is this geographic inquiry
process that they go through,

01:17:53.440 --> 01:17:57.000
and a lot of people who were
science teachers will look

01:17:57.000 --> 01:17:58.550
at this and say,
well, of course.

01:17:58.550 --> 01:17:59.850
Everybody's doing this.

01:17:59.850 --> 01:18:02.710
No, not everybody was doing
this, and certainly not

01:18:02.710 --> 01:18:04.040
so much social studies teachers.

01:18:04.040 --> 01:18:07.090
I was a social studies teacher,
but I grew up as a biologist,

01:18:07.090 --> 01:18:12.190
and so it's that science thing
that helps people see I need

01:18:12.190 --> 01:18:14.810
to be approaching these
things scientifically.

01:18:14.810 --> 01:18:18.920
I always wanted my kids to be
exploring and messing with data,

01:18:18.920 --> 01:18:22.500
and that's what you got
to do with these tools.

01:18:22.500 --> 01:18:25.170
Well, and that's what happened
with some of the materials,

01:18:25.170 --> 01:18:26.530
the software, but started coming

01:18:26.530 --> 01:18:32.830
out for integrating both
desktop data and online data.

01:18:32.830 --> 01:18:36.500
So, you can see in the far
right, Arc Explore Java Edition

01:18:36.500 --> 01:18:39.860
for Education that
came out in 2007,

01:18:39.860 --> 01:18:44.130
and then ArcGIS Explorer,
and then, okay.

01:18:44.130 --> 01:18:45.980
Come on, you can
scroll down here.

01:18:45.980 --> 01:18:47.280
Let's see.

01:18:47.280 --> 01:18:49.620
Let me smallerize this
one more a notch here.

01:18:49.620 --> 01:18:52.080
All right, then we can get to --

01:18:52.080 --> 01:18:54.500
how about if I move
the mouse over here?

01:18:54.500 --> 01:18:59.680
All right, well, we'll
just deal with that.

01:18:59.680 --> 01:19:05.250
ArcGIS Explorer, and then,
the ArcGIS online came out.

01:19:05.250 --> 01:19:08.880
And then, some apps
working with ArcGIS online.

01:19:08.880 --> 01:19:12.780
So, things were really
starting to happen at the end

01:19:12.780 --> 01:19:19.020
of these 2010-2011 year,
and in 2012, my God,

01:19:19.020 --> 01:19:22.270
the world just went -- exploded.

01:19:22.270 --> 01:19:25.660
ArcGIS Online organizations
came out, and people finally,

01:19:25.660 --> 01:19:30.130
in schools, had a way to have
students be able to safely

01:19:30.130 --> 01:19:35.030
and securely be able to share
and collaborate and work

01:19:35.030 --> 01:19:40.500
across activities, across
classrooms with each other.

01:19:40.500 --> 01:19:43.070
There were all kinds of ways
that they could do this,

01:19:43.070 --> 01:19:47.180
and Jack ran into
[inaudible], who introduced him

01:19:47.180 --> 01:19:49.830
to this school, and he
said, "I think we want

01:19:49.830 --> 01:19:51.130
to work with the school."

01:19:51.130 --> 01:19:55.130
And what they were able to do,
they had two fabulous teachers

01:19:55.130 --> 01:19:58.460
who were at this
math-science-technology

01:19:58.460 --> 01:19:59.760
magnet academy.

01:19:59.760 --> 01:20:02.900
It was the social studies
teacher and the English teacher

01:20:02.900 --> 01:20:05.270
who took GIS and ran with it,

01:20:05.270 --> 01:20:08.390
because they converted what
was already a great project,

01:20:08.390 --> 01:20:11.440
a research project, and to
a really powerful thing,

01:20:11.440 --> 01:20:14.950
and in three months,
they went from, okay,

01:20:14.950 --> 01:20:18.060
we now have computers we
can turn on two, Jack,

01:20:18.060 --> 01:20:21.270
this is the group that
needs to be up on stage.

01:20:21.270 --> 01:20:23.940
When you have teachers that
are really good teachers,

01:20:23.940 --> 01:20:27.850
and you expose them to GIS,
powerful things happen.

01:20:27.850 --> 01:20:31.030
And so, they came
onto the stage.

01:20:31.030 --> 01:20:34.370
They show people what was
possible, and that was

01:20:34.370 --> 01:20:36.810
about the time when President
Obama was saying, hey,

01:20:36.810 --> 01:20:40.280
we want private industry
to help education.

01:20:40.280 --> 01:20:41.740
Jack heard that said, okay.

01:20:41.740 --> 01:20:43.620
We're going to do that, and
as Candice was talking about,

01:20:43.620 --> 01:20:44.920
we're going to do that.

01:20:44.920 --> 01:20:49.480
We're going to provide software
to any school that wants it.

01:20:49.480 --> 01:20:50.980
We're going to provide mentors.

01:20:50.980 --> 01:20:52.730
We're going to provide
instructional materials,

01:20:52.730 --> 01:20:54.790
and we're going to provide
some teacher support.

01:20:54.790 --> 01:20:57.180
So, we're going to
make that stuff happen,

01:20:57.180 --> 01:21:02.010
and that was this Connect
Ed program that started out,

01:21:02.010 --> 01:21:08.770
and as we jumped in in 2014, and
the biggest thing that we jumped

01:21:08.770 --> 01:21:12.330
into was working
with geo inquiries.

01:21:12.330 --> 01:21:16.470
One of my colleagues, Tom Baker,
said, okay, we've got to come

01:21:16.470 --> 01:21:21.230
up with materials that
Joe Teacher, Jane Teacher,

01:21:21.230 --> 01:21:25.820
without GIS background, can
incorporate into their class,

01:21:25.820 --> 01:21:27.960
into work that they're
already doing.

01:21:27.960 --> 01:21:30.040
So, he has, over the
last couple years,

01:21:30.040 --> 01:21:35.950
built with teachers helping him
out, built in these nine sets

01:21:35.950 --> 01:21:42.570
of 15 to 20 lessons for anybody
to use with no GIS background.

01:21:42.570 --> 01:21:44.000
So, how do they work?

01:21:44.000 --> 01:21:48.650
Well, what happens is
there is a two-page,

01:21:48.650 --> 01:21:52.930
back and front PDF
for every lesson.

01:21:52.930 --> 01:21:57.380
That two-page PDF includes a
color bar on the first page

01:21:57.380 --> 01:22:02.400
where it's got a URL to its
own unique preconstructed map.

01:22:02.400 --> 01:22:07.810
So, all of these lessons, 150
lessons, that lead to content

01:22:07.810 --> 01:22:11.150
that is the stuff that teachers
are doing in their standard,

01:22:11.150 --> 01:22:13.800
regular classroom activities.

01:22:13.800 --> 01:22:15.820
They're working on
standard content.

01:22:15.820 --> 01:22:17.480
So, it's Edgar Allan Poe.

01:22:17.480 --> 01:22:23.310
It's the Civil War, or it's
earthquakes and plate tectonics

01:22:23.310 --> 01:22:29.280
and watersheds and linear
rates of development

01:22:29.280 --> 01:22:31.190
and whatever happens to be.

01:22:31.190 --> 01:22:32.970
Oh, and there's elementary

01:22:32.970 --> 01:22:36.330
that is an integrated
set of content, as well.

01:22:36.330 --> 01:22:39.410
Teachers can do this with
very little background,

01:22:39.410 --> 01:22:43.440
and it'll work even in just
one computer in a classroom

01:22:43.440 --> 01:22:46.440
with a projector, but
if you have students

01:22:46.440 --> 01:22:49.850
that have devices,
all the better.

01:22:49.850 --> 01:22:53.150
And so, this has been
extremely powerful,

01:22:53.150 --> 01:22:55.510
because no login is required.

01:22:55.510 --> 01:23:00.080
They can do this in 15 minutes,
or if they decide, oh, hey,

01:23:00.080 --> 01:23:02.220
we want to mess around
with the software,

01:23:02.220 --> 01:23:04.410
it may take a little bit longer.

01:23:04.410 --> 01:23:06.250
But it's all good.

01:23:06.250 --> 01:23:08.660
Now what has come of that?

01:23:08.660 --> 01:23:12.290
You introduce people to
some of these geo inquiries

01:23:12.290 --> 01:23:16.800
where they get to do these
activities, and they say, great.

01:23:16.800 --> 01:23:18.120
I want more.

01:23:18.120 --> 01:23:19.420
Where's more?

01:23:19.420 --> 01:23:20.890
Well, a level two.

01:23:20.890 --> 01:23:24.480
So, we've been creating
these level-two geo inquiries

01:23:24.480 --> 01:23:29.180
that say now we want you to
get into doing some analysis.

01:23:29.180 --> 01:23:31.380
To do that, you actually
have to log

01:23:31.380 --> 01:23:34.780
in with an organization
account and be able

01:23:34.780 --> 01:23:39.960
to have publishing capacity,
but when you can do that,

01:23:39.960 --> 01:23:42.810
you can do geographic analysis.

01:23:42.810 --> 01:23:47.170
So, this particular lesson,
this dustbowl, is looking at --

01:23:47.170 --> 01:23:52.100
it's a summarize within
activity, where you're going in

01:23:52.100 --> 01:23:55.210
and taking a look at how
many are within this zone.

01:23:55.210 --> 01:23:59.500
And so, there are all kinds
of analytical capacities

01:23:59.500 --> 01:24:03.290
that are built into ArcGIS
online, and what's happening is

01:24:03.290 --> 01:24:06.320
that teachers are starting
to get exposed to this

01:24:06.320 --> 01:24:07.650
and discovering, while.

01:24:07.650 --> 01:24:09.040
This is pretty powerful.

01:24:09.040 --> 01:24:13.150
This is pretty cool, and those
organizations are available

01:24:13.150 --> 01:24:15.770
at no cost to any
school in the country,

01:24:15.770 --> 01:24:18.090
and that's what a lot
of schools are doing.

01:24:18.090 --> 01:24:25.830
So then, what you
see is a couple

01:24:25.830 --> 01:24:27.130
of different examples here.

01:24:27.130 --> 01:24:29.820
So, in the bottom right,
let's start with that one.

01:24:29.820 --> 01:24:33.960
Here you see an AP
human geography class

01:24:33.960 --> 01:24:38.220
that is happening in two
schools at once with one teacher

01:24:38.220 --> 01:24:43.080
that is a virtual situation
in the other school.

01:24:43.080 --> 01:24:46.020
So, you can see the other
school in the left-hand monitor,

01:24:46.020 --> 01:24:50.790
and you can see the presentation
that he's walking his students

01:24:50.790 --> 01:24:56.950
through in two schools at
once, just with a big monitor.

01:24:56.950 --> 01:24:58.770
That's very doable, even

01:24:58.770 --> 01:25:00.990
if you don't have a really
big monitor like that.

01:25:00.990 --> 01:25:02.580
This was a very cool classroom.

01:25:02.580 --> 01:25:03.880
I love this.

01:25:03.880 --> 01:25:06.190
And you can see, actually,
if you get in and take a look

01:25:06.190 --> 01:25:09.670
at it, the students all have
devices on their machines.

01:25:09.670 --> 01:25:12.300
So, he's walked them
through some things,

01:25:12.300 --> 01:25:13.600
and now he's saying, okay,

01:25:13.600 --> 01:25:15.210
here's what I want
you to explore.

01:25:15.210 --> 01:25:17.650
So, now in three
different classrooms

01:25:17.650 --> 01:25:19.630
in these other pictures,
you're seeing students,

01:25:19.630 --> 01:25:22.150
and they're all working
on iPads here.

01:25:22.150 --> 01:25:25.360
The fellow with the broken
arm in the top-left corner,

01:25:25.360 --> 01:25:28.190
he's actually got
the teacher material

01:25:28.190 --> 01:25:30.050
that he's been working with.

01:25:30.050 --> 01:25:32.950
And this teacher said,
hey, I like my science kids

01:25:32.950 --> 01:25:37.260
to be working with the actual
content that I get to see.

01:25:37.260 --> 01:25:39.610
I want them to go
through the exact steps,

01:25:39.610 --> 01:25:41.570
and we interrupt them
every now and then.

01:25:41.570 --> 01:25:45.830
And so, he was very good,
skilled at doing that.

01:25:45.830 --> 01:25:49.410
The student below in the
lower left, he's working

01:25:49.410 --> 01:25:53.610
on a social studies one,
looking at the Middle East,

01:25:53.610 --> 01:25:55.890
with a worksheet
from the teacher

01:25:55.890 --> 01:25:59.270
that the teacher has specially
created and said, you know,

01:25:59.270 --> 01:26:02.830
go through these activities
and work your way through it.

01:26:02.830 --> 01:26:05.680
And the student on the top
right has no worksheet at all.

01:26:05.680 --> 01:26:08.560
That student and that
class, they're going through

01:26:08.560 --> 01:26:10.960
and saying, hey, this is
what we want you to explore.

01:26:10.960 --> 01:26:13.130
You've got 10 minutes
to get in and explore

01:26:13.130 --> 01:26:15.290
and tell me what you
found afterwards.

01:26:15.290 --> 01:26:18.110
And so, there are a lot of
different ways of working

01:26:18.110 --> 01:26:20.960
with these things,
teaching standard content.

01:26:20.960 --> 01:26:23.810
So that's been very helpful,
and people get to the end

01:26:23.810 --> 01:26:25.110
of that and they say, great.

01:26:25.110 --> 01:26:26.410
I want more.

01:26:26.410 --> 01:26:27.710
Where do I go?

01:26:27.710 --> 01:26:29.010
So, people inside Esri

01:26:29.010 --> 01:26:33.260
and beyond have been
building these materials.

01:26:33.260 --> 01:26:37.070
There's a book that came
out, the ArcGIS book,

01:26:37.070 --> 01:26:41.050
and what that says is it
provides people a number

01:26:41.050 --> 01:26:44.270
of activities that
they can go through.

01:26:44.270 --> 01:26:50.370
Well, they've added to that some
lessons that they also said,

01:26:50.370 --> 01:26:53.630
hey, let's open it up
and bring some lessons

01:26:53.630 --> 01:26:55.480
that are just designed
for teachers.

01:26:55.480 --> 01:26:57.650
And so, there are three
different types of lessons,

01:26:57.650 --> 01:26:59.990
and one of the mentors
said, "My God,

01:26:59.990 --> 01:27:02.700
the kids are just downloading
the book or the lesson

01:27:02.700 --> 01:27:04.270
on to their phone,
and they're doing it

01:27:04.270 --> 01:27:06.460
on the computers,
and they love it.

01:27:06.460 --> 01:27:07.760
They're focused.

01:27:07.760 --> 01:27:09.670
They're so into it,"
which is great.

01:27:09.670 --> 01:27:11.510
That's what we want
people to do.

01:27:11.510 --> 01:27:14.630
And one of the best examples of
that is happening in Virginia,

01:27:14.630 --> 01:27:18.380
where the Virginia Geospatial
Semester, which is a program

01:27:18.380 --> 01:27:21.720
that is coordinated by
James Madison University,

01:27:21.720 --> 01:27:27.830
is running through and they've
got about 500 students this year

01:27:27.830 --> 01:27:29.130
that are going through that.

01:27:29.130 --> 01:27:30.430
Mostly 12th graders.

01:27:30.430 --> 01:27:32.350
There are a few 11th
graders going through it.

01:27:32.350 --> 01:27:36.620
Science, social studies,
and some CTE teachers.

01:27:36.620 --> 01:27:40.260
But that's not the
only way to do that.

01:27:40.260 --> 01:27:42.360
There are also people,

01:27:42.360 --> 01:27:44.930
as Congressman was talking
about, the East Initiative.

01:27:44.930 --> 01:27:48.440
So, these folks are working
through, in Arkansas,

01:27:48.440 --> 01:27:51.410
there are 250 schools
in Arkansas

01:27:51.410 --> 01:27:53.500
that are participating
in this program.

01:27:53.500 --> 01:27:57.310
It is a project-based,
high-tech,

01:27:57.310 --> 01:28:00.600
individualized service
learning project.

01:28:00.600 --> 01:28:02.920
And so, people are going
through and learning GIS.

01:28:02.920 --> 01:28:05.780
High schools, most high
schools in Arkansas,

01:28:05.780 --> 01:28:08.270
many middle schools, and a few,

01:28:08.270 --> 01:28:11.400
even elementary schools,
kids are doing GIS.

01:28:11.400 --> 01:28:14.390
And so, you can see some
map-based activities

01:28:14.390 --> 01:28:19.040
in the example on the website,
but a lot of students are going

01:28:19.040 --> 01:28:20.960
through and just exploring it.

01:28:20.960 --> 01:28:23.960
The two kids that are over here
on the left, munchkins again.

01:28:23.960 --> 01:28:28.560
Fourth-graders who were up on
stage in 2014 doing something,

01:28:28.560 --> 01:28:32.500
and they showed it, and
those kids saying, hey,

01:28:32.500 --> 01:28:37.530
we took our balloon data,
and let's display it in 3D,

01:28:37.530 --> 01:28:39.150
and let's make a movie of it.

01:28:39.150 --> 01:28:40.560
And people came up
to me afterwards

01:28:40.560 --> 01:28:43.480
and said the students are
doing things that we don't do.

01:28:43.480 --> 01:28:46.190
So once again, yep,
you can do it,

01:28:46.190 --> 01:28:48.410
if you just get the
chance to do it.

01:28:48.410 --> 01:28:52.940
And in Michigan, the Grace
Program was a very powerful

01:28:52.940 --> 01:28:55.460
thing that said we want to
start with the teachers learning

01:28:55.460 --> 01:28:57.450
about this through
geo inquiries.

01:28:57.450 --> 01:29:00.030
Mentor them to go beyond that.

01:29:00.030 --> 01:29:04.210
Maybe inspire the teachers
to get the students

01:29:04.210 --> 01:29:06.450
to do some additional training,

01:29:06.450 --> 01:29:09.740
and then the savvy kids can
qualify for internships.

01:29:09.740 --> 01:29:13.580
And they had about 150 or
200 kids over the last couple

01:29:13.580 --> 01:29:17.560
of years get summer internships,
paid summer internships

01:29:17.560 --> 01:29:18.860
with what they're doing.

01:29:18.860 --> 01:29:22.840
And there's a little town in
Michigan where there is a kid

