01:33:22.400 --> 01:33:23.700
&gt;&gt; Kathleen McGuigan:
Good morning.

01:33:23.700 --> 01:33:26.670
My name's Kathy McGuigan,
and I work in the learning

01:33:26.670 --> 01:33:29.720
and innovation team, and we're
part of the new center here

01:33:29.720 --> 01:33:33.110
at the library, which is
called the Center for Learning,

01:33:33.110 --> 01:33:37.030
Literacy, and Engagement,
and I do have the pleasure

01:33:37.030 --> 01:33:39.500
of building teacher
programs and products

01:33:39.500 --> 01:33:43.480
for educators using
libraries' collections,

01:33:43.480 --> 01:33:46.210
that's what I'm going to talk
about a little bit today,

01:33:46.210 --> 01:33:52.360
a project that we started last
summer looking at literary maps.

01:33:52.360 --> 01:33:54.000
Excuse me.

01:33:54.000 --> 01:33:57.990
So, what we're looking at are
some of the foundational steps

01:33:57.990 --> 01:34:03.090
that we're taking to visualize
the library's catalog for,

01:34:03.090 --> 01:34:06.620
and we're really focusing
on American literature,

01:34:06.620 --> 01:34:10.270
and I'll go into a little
bit more of the specifics.

01:34:10.270 --> 01:34:13.700
But I was very excited to hear
from our past two speakers

01:34:13.700 --> 01:34:17.360
about the mentoring aspect
to this and the access

01:34:17.360 --> 01:34:20.750
that schools will have,
because really, what I'm talking

01:34:20.750 --> 01:34:23.220
to the -- the audience I'm
talking to you today, really,

01:34:23.220 --> 01:34:25.500
are the educators in
the crowd and talking

01:34:25.500 --> 01:34:29.520
about how I'm approaching
this project

01:34:29.520 --> 01:34:32.260
from the educator perspective.

01:34:32.260 --> 01:34:36.160
So, what is a literary map?

01:34:36.160 --> 01:34:39.990
A literary map is a
map, or it's a picture,

01:34:39.990 --> 01:34:42.900
that acknowledges the
contributions of authors

01:34:42.900 --> 01:34:46.480
to a specific area or region.

01:34:46.480 --> 01:34:54.470
It can also be a map, or
a picture, of locations

01:34:54.470 --> 01:34:56.800
of works within fiction.

01:34:56.800 --> 01:35:01.590
So, I want to show you
a couple of examples

01:35:01.590 --> 01:35:05.440
of some literary maps that we
have here in the collection

01:35:05.440 --> 01:35:10.180
at the Library of Congress in
our Geography and Maps Division.

01:35:10.180 --> 01:35:14.660
So, this map is the
pictorial chart

01:35:14.660 --> 01:35:18.910
of American Literature
from 1932.

01:35:20.380 --> 01:35:26.030
And this is a Book Lovers map
of the United States from 1949.

01:35:28.060 --> 01:35:32.690
Next up is the Iowa
literary map from 1934

01:35:32.690 --> 01:35:34.850
from the Davenport Library.

01:35:34.850 --> 01:35:41.820
And here we have the Texas
literary map of 1955,

01:35:41.820 --> 01:35:45.100
and this comes from the
Dallas Public Library.

01:35:45.100 --> 01:35:50.080
And lastly, in terms
of our examples,

01:35:50.080 --> 01:35:54.360
this is the Maine Writers
map, and this comes

01:35:54.360 --> 01:35:57.140
from the Maine Council
of Teachers of English,

01:35:57.140 --> 01:36:00.660
and this is from 1981.

01:36:00.660 --> 01:36:08.280
So, in approaching this
project, there was, in 1993,

01:36:08.280 --> 01:36:10.230
there was an exhibition
here at the Library

01:36:10.230 --> 01:36:12.510
of Congress called
Language of the Land,

01:36:12.510 --> 01:36:16.980
Journey into Literary America,
where these literary maps

01:36:16.980 --> 01:36:21.170
that the library houses
were put onto display,

01:36:21.170 --> 01:36:27.600
and this exhibition went on the
road and traveled to 16 states

01:36:27.600 --> 01:36:32.740
and 20 different sites, and
as part of their programming,

01:36:32.740 --> 01:36:34.610
state centers for the
book, and I'll get

01:36:34.610 --> 01:36:36.910
into what a State
Center for the Book is.

01:36:36.910 --> 01:36:40.310
They started producing
literary maps.

01:36:40.310 --> 01:36:44.560
And then, those maps, as well as
other maps from the collections,

01:36:44.560 --> 01:36:48.190
are in this particular book,
which is called the same

01:36:48.190 --> 01:36:50.100
as the exhibition
Language of the Land,

01:36:50.100 --> 01:36:52.100
Journeys into Literary America.

01:36:52.100 --> 01:36:55.440
This was published in 1999.

01:36:55.440 --> 01:37:00.080
And so, when I learned
about the literary maps here

01:37:00.080 --> 01:37:04.620
at the Library of Congress, it's
something that has really stuck

01:37:04.620 --> 01:37:06.730
in my head since I've been here.

01:37:06.730 --> 01:37:11.280
I've been here for 11
years, and a long time ago,

01:37:11.280 --> 01:37:13.040
I was an English teacher, right?

01:37:13.040 --> 01:37:17.000
And so, I was thinking about
how you could use these

01:37:17.000 --> 01:37:20.770
instructionally with your
students, but beyond that,

01:37:20.770 --> 01:37:27.030
in looking at some of the maps,
right, figuring out the folks

01:37:27.030 --> 01:37:29.890
who selected the authors
that are displayed

01:37:29.890 --> 01:37:33.070
on this map may look very
different to your students,

01:37:33.070 --> 01:37:36.110
in terms of building
their own literary map

01:37:36.110 --> 01:37:41.180
and celebrating different facets
of their literary history.

01:37:41.180 --> 01:37:44.080
So, last year, I had
the pleasure of working

01:37:44.080 --> 01:37:47.440
for the Center for the Book,
which is also in the Center

01:37:47.440 --> 01:37:51.260
for Learning Literacy
and Engagement,

01:37:51.260 --> 01:37:57.410
and as part of that work,
the state centers --

01:37:57.410 --> 01:38:01.900
we have a state center for
the book in all 50 states,

01:38:01.900 --> 01:38:05.880
and they are about reading
promotion, literacy promotion,

01:38:05.880 --> 01:38:07.580
and celebrating poetry.

01:38:07.580 --> 01:38:10.090
So, taking some pieces
of the programming

01:38:10.090 --> 01:38:15.910
that the library does on behalf
of constituents and rolls them

01:38:15.910 --> 01:38:17.300
out through the state.

01:38:17.300 --> 01:38:22.370
And so, several states had
mentioned that they were looking

01:38:22.370 --> 01:38:26.040
at using GIS to do
their literary maps.

01:38:26.040 --> 01:38:30.430
And so, what we decided to do
was to form a committee, right?

01:38:30.430 --> 01:38:32.040
That's what you do.

01:38:32.040 --> 01:38:36.070
So, we formed a committee
with several of the states

01:38:36.070 --> 01:38:39.890
who were already in this
field looking at this project

01:38:39.890 --> 01:38:44.400
and how you take your literary
map from a paper product

01:38:44.400 --> 01:38:47.110
and map that out using GIS.

01:38:47.110 --> 01:38:51.930
So, we're working with the
state of Illinois, Mississippi,

01:38:51.930 --> 01:38:58.390
Pennsylvania, Washington,
Minnesota, and Montana.

01:38:58.390 --> 01:39:04.920
And so, I just want to
show you a quick example.

01:39:04.920 --> 01:39:09.910
This is a project from Montana
and the Montana Authors Project.

01:39:09.910 --> 01:39:12.960
And really, what they did
is just mapped out the books

01:39:12.960 --> 01:39:17.350
that they selected from
their physical literary map

01:39:17.350 --> 01:39:20.320
and mapped it out using GIS.

01:39:20.320 --> 01:39:21.620
This is another project.

01:39:21.620 --> 01:39:23.850
This is the Washington
State Center for the Book,

01:39:23.850 --> 01:39:26.860
and this is called Finding
Books in Washington.

01:39:26.860 --> 01:39:30.280
And so, they were looking at it
from an end-user's perspective.

01:39:30.280 --> 01:39:32.170
How do they serve
their constituents

01:39:32.170 --> 01:39:33.470
in getting access to books?

01:39:33.470 --> 01:39:35.650
So, they've mapped out
the public, academic,

01:39:35.650 --> 01:39:37.550
and tribal libraries, as well

01:39:37.550 --> 01:39:40.700
as independent bookstores
throughout the state.

01:39:40.700 --> 01:39:42.240
And then, the last
example I want

01:39:42.240 --> 01:39:44.660
to show here is the
Illinois Center for the Book.

01:39:44.660 --> 01:39:48.900
They have a very robust
database that they maintain,

01:39:48.900 --> 01:39:51.520
which is called the
Illinois Writers Project.

01:39:51.520 --> 01:39:56.610
And not only does the state
center nominate writers to be

01:39:56.610 --> 01:39:59.320
in the Illinois Writers Project,

01:39:59.320 --> 01:40:03.110
but writers themselves
can self-selected nominate

01:40:03.110 --> 01:40:05.060
themselves for the
Writers Project.

01:40:05.060 --> 01:40:09.150
So, you can see, this
is a very dense project.

01:40:09.150 --> 01:40:12.740
So, one of the things
that we did in meeting

01:40:12.740 --> 01:40:18.140
with the groups is to really
map out one of the paper maps

01:40:18.140 --> 01:40:21.430
and map it out on
the Esri platform.

01:40:21.430 --> 01:40:23.770
And so, here you can see
a side-by-side comparison.

01:40:23.770 --> 01:40:26.780
I'm not sure how big this
is actually showing up,

01:40:26.780 --> 01:40:31.360
but this is the Arizona Literary
map, and it is then laid

01:40:31.360 --> 01:40:35.450
out for looking at
the catalogue records

01:40:35.450 --> 01:40:37.580
that we have here
at the library.

01:40:37.580 --> 01:40:42.070
And it was just the start
what I'm going to be talking

01:40:42.070 --> 01:40:45.980
about in mapping this out.

01:40:45.980 --> 01:40:49.950
I know you all know this,
but I just want to talk

01:40:49.950 --> 01:40:53.740
about the benefits of doing
something like this is

01:40:53.740 --> 01:40:59.600
that we can talk about
exact geographic location.

01:40:59.600 --> 01:41:04.690
And this becomes more
accessible to a larger audience.

01:41:04.690 --> 01:41:08.790
Again, if you take one of those
physical maps, a literary map,

01:41:08.790 --> 01:41:13.450
students might not recognize
themselves within those writers,

01:41:13.450 --> 01:41:17.620
within that particular area,
and if you put it into the hands

01:41:17.620 --> 01:41:21.040
of the students to determine
what facets they would use

01:41:21.040 --> 01:41:25.300
to lay out their own map, you
know in using the Esri platform

01:41:25.300 --> 01:41:27.800
and GIS in particular,
it's a matter

01:41:27.800 --> 01:41:30.910
of easily editing
the information,

01:41:30.910 --> 01:41:34.400
and most importantly, you
can incorporate large amounts

01:41:34.400 --> 01:41:35.700
of data.

01:41:35.700 --> 01:41:38.080
So, and I'll get into
a little bit more

01:41:38.080 --> 01:41:41.420
of what we're looking at here.

01:41:41.420 --> 01:41:45.540
And it serves as an
intuitive educational tool,

01:41:45.540 --> 01:41:50.000
as our last two speakers
have talked to you about.

01:41:50.000 --> 01:41:54.480
So, looking at the
library's records.

01:41:54.480 --> 01:42:02.370
In 2017, the library
released 25 million records

01:42:02.370 --> 01:42:06.640
of their catalog, and
as part of that release,

01:42:06.640 --> 01:42:10.420
what they did was they
also sponsored a hackathon,

01:42:10.420 --> 01:42:15.120
where they invited groups
in and at their sites

01:42:15.120 --> 01:42:18.800
to start taking a
look at the data.

01:42:18.800 --> 01:42:26.570
And so, there was a lot of
great work that was done,

01:42:26.570 --> 01:42:31.710
in terms of being able
to look at what is needed

01:42:31.710 --> 01:42:36.760
to extract the data
within those sets.

01:42:36.760 --> 01:42:39.790
And we know within
the MARC records.

01:42:39.790 --> 01:42:43.500
So, what is a MARC record, for
those who are not familiar?

01:42:43.500 --> 01:42:46.360
It's a machine-readable
cataloging record.

01:42:46.360 --> 01:42:52.580
So, it's the basis of the
collections here at the library.

01:42:52.580 --> 01:42:56.520
And within the fields,
and I'm not a librarian.

01:42:56.520 --> 01:42:58.920
So, for the librarians
in the crowd,

01:42:58.920 --> 01:43:01.660
I just want to put
that out there.

01:43:01.660 --> 01:43:09.170
So, but there is a field within
the MARC records, which is 651,

01:43:09.170 --> 01:43:14.120
and that is a field that locates
where the work takes place.

01:43:14.120 --> 01:43:17.590
So, if we were to look at all
of the geographical information

01:43:17.590 --> 01:43:20.260
within a MARC record,
you would have the place

01:43:20.260 --> 01:43:22.090
where books are published.

01:43:22.090 --> 01:43:24.520
That is actually
in the MARC record,

01:43:24.520 --> 01:43:26.830
but you would see
a great influx,

01:43:26.830 --> 01:43:30.110
if you were taking a look at
American fictional records

01:43:30.110 --> 01:43:32.160
with that in New York.

01:43:32.160 --> 01:43:34.380
So, what we're really
trying to take a look at is

01:43:34.380 --> 01:43:37.690
where does the work
of fiction take place?

01:43:37.690 --> 01:43:40.670
And that happens
within these MARC tags,

01:43:40.670 --> 01:43:44.180
and in particular, in field 651.

01:43:44.180 --> 01:43:46.960
So, this is the MARC
record for one

01:43:46.960 --> 01:43:50.520
of the most popular novels
that's taught in schools,

01:43:50.520 --> 01:43:52.780
which is The Great
Gatsby, right?

01:43:52.780 --> 01:43:55.930
And so, taking a look
at the MARC record

01:43:55.930 --> 01:44:00.320
for The Great Gatsby,
we get to field 651,

01:44:00.320 --> 01:44:03.780
and as you would expect, it
says Long Island, New York.

01:44:03.780 --> 01:44:08.260
So, taking that one step
further, mapping it out,

01:44:08.260 --> 01:44:11.600
this is transcribing the
MARC record and putting it

01:44:11.600 --> 01:44:15.790
on to -- into the map.

01:44:15.790 --> 01:44:22.000
So, in talking about how do we
move forward with this project?

01:44:22.000 --> 01:44:26.980
And again, when you start
looking at the amount of data

01:44:26.980 --> 01:44:29.710
that is out there with
the 25 million records,

01:44:29.710 --> 01:44:32.100
how do you start
making sense of this?

01:44:32.100 --> 01:44:35.550
And so, there are so many smart
people here at the library,

01:44:35.550 --> 01:44:37.460
and several of them
are in the room,

01:44:37.460 --> 01:44:40.110
and I want to thank you all for
helping me with this project.

01:44:40.110 --> 01:44:44.300
So, I sat down and talked
with a number of experts

01:44:44.300 --> 01:44:47.060
within the library, and
someone made the suggestion,

01:44:47.060 --> 01:44:48.460
you should get a junior fellow.

01:44:48.460 --> 01:44:51.640
This is an intern that comes
and spends six or seven weeks

01:44:51.640 --> 01:44:56.820
with us here at the library,
and just invite this person

01:44:56.820 --> 01:44:59.150
in to start taking
a look at the --

