that he did was to take a look

01:45:40.750 --> 01:45:46.780
at all of the data sets and
focus in on one of the parts.

01:45:46.780 --> 01:45:51.860
So, those 25 million records
are in 41 different parts.

01:45:51.860 --> 01:45:59.090
And so, we narrowed that 41
parts down to part 41, and so,

01:45:59.090 --> 01:46:02.040
what he did is started
editing the data

01:46:02.040 --> 01:46:05.820
within that using a
tool called MARCEdit,

01:46:05.820 --> 01:46:07.120
and then he refined this.

01:46:07.120 --> 01:46:11.070
For those GIS professionals in
the room, you know far better

01:46:11.070 --> 01:46:16.330
than I do how much time it takes
to really get into the data sets

01:46:16.330 --> 01:46:18.980
and make sure that
they are consistent,

01:46:18.980 --> 01:46:23.190
and then translated them
and cleaned up the records,

01:46:23.190 --> 01:46:25.910
and then, finally,
mapped them out.

01:46:25.910 --> 01:46:30.150
So, we did not get
anywhere near mapping

01:46:30.150 --> 01:46:32.450
out the American fictional
records, but I will share

01:46:32.450 --> 01:46:34.820
with you what we
were able to do.

01:46:34.820 --> 01:46:40.860
So, the part 41 that
he was taking a look

01:46:40.860 --> 01:46:44.150
at had 250,000 records.

01:46:44.150 --> 01:46:46.400
And so, the processing
power that you need

01:46:46.400 --> 01:46:53.050
to even start refining the
data in this is pretty intense.

01:46:53.050 --> 01:46:59.590
And as I mentioned before, he
used MARCEdit to look at that.

01:46:59.590 --> 01:47:04.100
And then, he moved that from
MARCEdit into Open Refine.

01:47:04.100 --> 01:47:07.070
And doing these steps was just

01:47:07.070 --> 01:47:12.440
to assess how many records
had data in field 651,

01:47:12.440 --> 01:47:18.060
because it is not complete
at all, whatsoever.

01:47:18.060 --> 01:47:23.460
And more recent records may
have that data the way we want

01:47:23.460 --> 01:47:26.830
to ingest it, but older records,

01:47:26.830 --> 01:47:30.470
in some cases, will
not have that.

01:47:30.470 --> 01:47:38.100
So, then he brought it
into Excel, and we started

01:47:38.100 --> 01:47:40.010
to focus on Washington State.

01:47:40.010 --> 01:47:43.010
It was a manageable piece of
information that we could do

01:47:43.010 --> 01:47:47.180
in the six to seven weeks that
he was here in Washington.

01:47:47.180 --> 01:47:51.880
And so, we focused on the State
of Washington and identified

01:47:51.880 --> 01:47:53.820
where we could find information.

01:47:53.820 --> 01:47:58.250
In a lot of cases, you'll
see just Washington labeled

01:47:58.250 --> 01:48:03.330
and not a specific
area within Washington.

01:48:03.330 --> 01:48:09.430
So, what he did is then he
took the data and related out,

01:48:09.430 --> 01:48:13.560
and where we had
Washington identified,

01:48:13.560 --> 01:48:17.570
and his key here is
this particular area.

01:48:17.570 --> 01:48:21.880
This has 192 records,
because this just Washington.

01:48:21.880 --> 01:48:27.140
And then, the other
areas around the state

01:48:27.140 --> 01:48:33.240
where the actual
city is listed out.

01:48:33.240 --> 01:48:38.040
So, this is the translation,
and looking at the title,

01:48:38.040 --> 01:48:43.350
the author, the year published,
the geographic ID, and then,

01:48:43.350 --> 01:48:49.080
he went into another platform
and extracted the book cover,

01:48:49.080 --> 01:48:51.720
so that it can provide some kind

01:48:51.720 --> 01:48:56.810
of visualization
with the information.

01:48:56.810 --> 01:49:03.110
So, what did we learn after this
summer is that that processing

01:49:03.110 --> 01:49:07.060
that has to happen
with the 41 parts,

01:49:07.060 --> 01:49:12.080
we need a lot more
interns and a lot of them.

01:49:12.080 --> 01:49:14.970
So, I was actually very
excited to hear about the access

01:49:14.970 --> 01:49:18.770
that the schools might
have, in terms of being able

01:49:18.770 --> 01:49:22.870
to start looking at data sets.

01:49:22.870 --> 01:49:26.240
But we also need a
better understanding

01:49:26.240 --> 01:49:30.860
of the MARC records and the
cataloging language that is used

01:49:30.860 --> 01:49:34.100
within the 651 fields.

01:49:34.100 --> 01:49:36.380
And then, we're also looking

01:49:36.380 --> 01:49:38.850
at the commercial
databases that are out there.

01:49:38.850 --> 01:49:43.490
As I mentioned, Josh
