library information sciences.

01:50:58.200 --> 01:51:01.730
We'd really love to get
into the cataloging aspect

01:51:01.730 --> 01:51:04.240
to the project.

01:51:04.240 --> 01:51:07.610
And again, mentioning,
we will be examining some

01:51:07.610 --> 01:51:11.700
of the other databases,
and we'll start meeting

01:51:11.700 --> 01:51:13.340
with other potential end users.

01:51:13.340 --> 01:51:17.620
Again, we have the state
centers, which is one

01:51:17.620 --> 01:51:20.580
of the driving forces for
this project, in particular.

01:51:20.580 --> 01:51:25.550
But thinking about the students
that you work with and the folks

01:51:25.550 --> 01:51:29.600
who would be able to
implement making their own map,

01:51:29.600 --> 01:51:34.680
using the robust data
that we could provide.

01:51:34.680 --> 01:51:37.120
And we're thinking,
at this juncture --

01:51:37.120 --> 01:51:38.660
I'm not making any promises.

01:51:38.660 --> 01:51:41.260
I'm not even asking permission,

01:51:41.260 --> 01:51:44.000
but we're thinking
about crowdsourcing.

01:51:44.000 --> 01:51:47.530
There's a project that was
done with the DC Public Library

01:51:47.530 --> 01:51:51.050
that started in 2012, where
librarians were invited

01:51:51.050 --> 01:51:55.220
into their database to
pull out passages of books

01:51:55.220 --> 01:51:58.370
that took place in different
neighborhoods in Washington DC,

01:51:58.370 --> 01:52:00.300
and they were able
to map that out.

01:52:00.300 --> 01:52:03.070
It started in earnest in 2012.

01:52:03.070 --> 01:52:08.080
I think it's not as updated
as it was in the beginning

01:52:08.080 --> 01:52:12.370
of the project, but they
opened it up to library

01:52:12.370 --> 01:52:14.280
and librarian professionals

01:52:14.280 --> 01:52:19.490
to mark those records
for their needs.

01:52:19.490 --> 01:52:23.700
And so, we're trying to take a
look at what does crowdsourcing

01:52:23.700 --> 01:52:27.800
with this look like, and
what kind of information,

01:52:27.800 --> 01:52:32.630
potentially, we could get back,
versus, again, the information

01:52:32.630 --> 01:52:35.140
that becomes very
important for the library,

01:52:35.140 --> 01:52:38.670
in terms of its cataloging
and cataloging records.

01:52:38.670 --> 01:52:41.960
So, that's a little bit of what
we're looking at, but again,

01:52:41.960 --> 01:52:45.220
for the educators in the
crowd, I want you to be aware

01:52:45.220 --> 01:52:48.790
