So, there's a lot of ways
of thinking about how some

01:59:22.040 --> 01:59:27.120
of these additional exposures
can influence people's lives.

01:59:30.510 --> 02:00:36.500
[ Female Speaking off Mic ]

02:00:36.500 --> 02:00:42.290
&gt;&gt; Charlie Fitzpatrick: So,
standards, models, how are we,

02:00:42.290 --> 02:00:46.830
and I'll speak for Esri on
this, addressing the notion

02:00:46.830 --> 02:00:51.240
of meeting standards,
helping people cope

02:00:51.240 --> 02:00:56.510
with the ultimate flexible tool

02:00:56.510 --> 02:01:02.840
and less flexible
educational environment?

02:01:02.840 --> 02:01:08.190
The short answer is
we are a GIS company,

02:01:08.190 --> 02:01:10.380
not an education company.

02:01:10.380 --> 02:01:19.500
And so, as broadly applicable
as GIS is, as powerful as it is,

02:01:19.500 --> 02:01:24.350
we said we can't possibly
meet, the 2-1/2 of us

02:01:24.350 --> 02:01:28.630
on the K-12 team, can't
possibly meet the needs

02:01:28.630 --> 02:01:33.350
of the 50 million students
across the country.

02:01:33.350 --> 02:01:39.540
What we are trying to do is
to help educators recognize

02:01:39.540 --> 02:01:45.120
that they can use tools in
a lot of different ways.

02:01:45.120 --> 02:01:49.260
We have any number of situations

02:01:49.260 --> 02:01:53.260
where a really good
teacher working with GIS

02:01:53.260 --> 02:01:59.010
in this department is across
the hall from a teacher

02:01:59.010 --> 02:02:02.040
in the same department
who will not use GIS

02:02:02.040 --> 02:02:07.450
because the second teacher
says he or she needs to focus

02:02:07.450 --> 02:02:11.090
on the standards, even though
the first teacher says I'm using

02:02:11.090 --> 02:02:13.470
it to meet the standards.

02:02:13.470 --> 02:02:16.320
And so, there are all kinds
of situations that we run

02:02:16.320 --> 02:02:21.860
into where, you know, as the
Congressman was talking about.

02:02:21.860 --> 02:02:23.840
Standards are important.

02:02:23.840 --> 02:02:25.140
Standards are helpful.

02:02:25.140 --> 02:02:27.620
That's why we have
said are many of them,

02:02:27.620 --> 02:02:29.870
and it's always a
challenge to know

02:02:29.870 --> 02:02:31.520
which ones you're going to meet.

02:02:31.520 --> 02:02:34.230
There are a number of
people who say we can't look

02:02:34.230 --> 02:02:37.380
at geo inquiries, if they
don't have our state --

02:02:37.380 --> 02:02:39.720
we can even look at the document

02:02:39.720 --> 02:02:41.930
if it doesn't have
our state on it.

02:02:41.930 --> 02:02:45.520
If it has a national
standard, we can't use it.

02:02:45.520 --> 02:02:49.280
We can't. So, it's
really a challenge

02:02:49.280 --> 02:02:51.610
for the educational environment.

02:02:51.610 --> 02:02:55.740
One of the biggest pieces
that we have started

02:02:55.740 --> 02:02:58.830
to notice is a number of people

02:02:58.830 --> 02:03:04.560
who are saying we're feeling
empowered to be creative

02:03:04.560 --> 02:03:08.240
in the ways that
we meet standards,

02:03:08.240 --> 02:03:11.460
because there is no
one way to meet them,

02:03:11.460 --> 02:03:16.970
and GIS will adapt to do that.

