02:10:24.220 --> 02:10:27.420
and President Obama
signed it into law.

02:10:27.420 --> 02:10:30.500
For the first time, there
two dedicated authorizations

02:10:30.500 --> 02:10:35.200
in federal K-12 law dealing
with geography education.

02:10:35.200 --> 02:10:40.510
And so, hopefully, if Congress
redoes the K-12 law again,

02:10:40.510 --> 02:10:42.480
and those authorizations are
strengthened [speaking off mic]

02:10:42.480 --> 02:10:47.830
it's an opportunity for
geography to make more inroads

02:10:47.830 --> 02:10:52.430
in what we're doing in K-12
instruction around the country.

02:10:52.430 --> 02:10:55.810
So, you know, we need to tall
our local educators the stories

02:10:55.810 --> 02:11:02.160
about what, you know, GIS can do

02:11:02.160 --> 02:11:05.630
for students, for
spatial thinking.

02:11:05.630 --> 02:11:09.790
And, you know, we need to also
work with folks, you know,

02:11:09.790 --> 02:11:16.650
across the street here, so when
they do reauthorize a K-12 law

02:11:16.650 --> 02:11:17.950
again, and it's supposed

02:11:17.950 --> 02:11:19.600
to be potentially
considered next year.

02:11:19.600 --> 02:11:20.900
They need to think about
the importance, you know,

02:11:20.900 --> 02:11:22.200
what geography means in
workforce development.

02:11:22.200 --> 02:11:23.500
So, it's a multipronged
approach,

02:11:23.500 --> 02:11:24.800
and it's something that's
evolving and it's something

02:11:24.800 --> 02:11:26.180
that can really make an
impact on [speaking off mic].

